{"title_page": "Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9\n| image        = Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9 by Nadar.jpg\n| caption      = Eugene-Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9, photo by [[Nadar (photographer)|Nadar]].\n| birth_name   = Marie-Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1848|2|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Nice]], France\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1910|3|29|1848|2|25|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Paris]], France\n| occupation   = Diplomat, archaeologist, philanthropist and literary critic\n| movement     = \n| genre        = \n| notableworks = ''The Russian Novel'' (1886)\n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| signature    = \n}}\n'''Marie-Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior''', [[vicomte]] '''de Vog\u00fc\u00e9''' (25 February 1848 \u2013 29 March 1910) was a French diplomat, [[Orientalism|Orientalist]], travel writer, [[Archaeology|archaeologist]], philanthropist and literary critic.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Nice]], France, he served in the [[Franco-Prussian War]], and at the conclusion of the war entered the diplomatic service of the [[Third French Republic|Third Republic]], being appointed successively [[attach\u00e9]] to the [[legation]]s in the [[Ottoman Empire]] and [[Egypt under Muhammad Ali and his successors|Egypt]], then secretary to the embassy in [[Saint Petersburg]].<ref>Gosse, Edmund (1913). [https://archive.org/stream/portraitssketche00goss#page/240/mode/2up \"Eug\u00e8ne Melchior de Vogu\u00e9.\"] In: ''Portraits and Sketches.'' London: William Heinemann, p. 250.</ref> He resigned in 1882,<ref>Gosse (1913), p. 254.</ref> and from 1893 to 1898 served as representative of [[Ard\u00e8che]] to the [[French National Assembly]].<ref>Gosse (1913), p. 264.</ref>\n\nHis connection with the ''[[Revue des deux mondes]]'' began in 1873 with his ''Voyage en Syrie et en Palestine'', and subsequently he was a frequent contributor. He did much to awaken French interest in the intellectual life of other countries, especially of [[Imperial Russia|Russia]], his sympathy with which was strengthened by his marriage in 1878 with a Russian lady, the sister of [[General Michael Nicolaivitch Annenkoff]]; De Vog\u00fc\u00e9 was practically the first to draw French attention to [[Fyodor Dostoyevsky]]. Many consider de Vog\u00fc\u00e9's essay to be the first major examination of the novelist's work.<ref>R\u00f6hl, Magnus (1976). ''Le Roman Russe de Eug\u00e8ne Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9.'' Stockholm: Almqvist & Wiksell.</ref>\n\nEug\u00e8ne-Melchior was also a brother-in-law of [[Karl de Struve]], Russian Ambassador to Japan, the United States, and the Netherlands.\n\nHe became a member of the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] in 1888.  His uncle, [[Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9]], also served in the academy concurrently for a few years.\n\nIn 1897, he wrote a short series of books concerning the [[War of the Spanish Succession]].\n\n==Works==\n* (1876). ''Syrie, Palestine, Mont Athos'' [https://archive.org/details/syriepalestinem00voggoog (1887 edition).]\n* (1877). ''Vangheli.''\n* (1879). ''Boulacq et Saqquarah.''\n* (1879). ''Chez les Pharaons.''\n* (1879). ''[https://archive.org/details/histoiresorient01voggoog Histoires Orientales.]''\n* (1883). ''Les Portraits du Si\u00e8cle.''\n* (1884). ''Le Fils de Pierre le Grand.''\n* (1884). ''Mazeppa''.\n* (1884). ''Un Changement de R\u00e8gne.''\n* (1885). ''[https://archive.org/details/histoiresdhiver00voggoog Histoires d\u2019Hiver.]''\n* (1886). ''Le Roman Russe.''\n* (1887). ''Souvenirs et Visions.''\n* (1888). ''Le Portrait du Louvre.''\n* (1889). [https://archive.org/stream/remarquessurlexp00vogu#page/n5/mode/2up ''Remarques sur l\u2019Exposition du Centenaire.]''\n* (1890). ''Le Manteau de Joseph Olenine.''\n* (1891). [https://archive.org/stream/spectaclescontem00voguoft#page/n7/mode/2up ''Spectacles Contemporains.'']\n* (1892). [https://archive.org/stream/regardshistoriqu00voguoft#page/n7/mode/2up ''Regards Historiques et Litt\u00e9raires.'']<ref>Bir\u00e9, Edmond (1890). [https://archive.org/stream/histoireetlitt00bir#page/340/mode/2up \"Un Acad\u00e9micien d'Aujourd'hui: Le Vicomte Melchior de Vogu\u00e9.\"] In: '' Histoire et Litt\u00e9rature.'' Lyon: Librairie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale Catholique et Classique, pp. 341\u2013357.</ref>\n* (1892). ''Heures d\u2019Histoire.''\n* (1893). ''C\u0153urs Russes.''\n* (1893). ''Notes sur le Bas-Vivarais.''\n* (1896). ''[https://archive.org/details/devantlesicle00voggoog Devant le Si\u00e8cle.]''\n* (1897). [https://archive.org/stream/jeandagrve00vog#page/n5/mode/2up ''Jean d\u2019Agr\u00e8ve.'']\n* (1898). ''[https://archive.org/details/histoireetposie00voggoog Histoire et Po\u00e9sie.]''\n* (1899). ''Les Morts qui Parlent (Sc\u00e8nes de la Vie Parlementaire).\n* (1900). ''Le Rappel des Ombres.''\n* (1902). ''Pages d\u2019Histoire''.\n* (1903). ''Le Ma\u00eetre de la Mer''.\n* (1904). ''Sous l\u2019Horizon: Hommes et Choses d\u2019Hier.''\n* (1905). ''[https://archive.org/details/maximegorkyloeu01voggoog Maxime Gorki.]''\n* (1910). [https://archive.org/stream/lesroutesprfpa00vog#page/n5/mode/2up ''Les Routes.'']\n\n'''Selected articles'''\n* (1894). [https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Un_Regard_en_arri\u00e8re_-_Les_Terroristes_russes \"Un Regard en Arri\u00e8re \u2014 Les Terroristes Russes,\"] ''Revue des Deux Mondes'', Vol. 122.\n* (1894). [https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Le_Dernier_livre_de_Taine \"Le Dernier Livre de Taine,\"] ''Revue des Deux Mondes'', Vol. 122.\n* (1894). [https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/\u00c0_propos_d'un_d\u00e9bat_religieux \"\u00c0 Propos d\u2019un D\u00e9bat Religieux,\"] ''Revue des Deux Mondes'', Vol. 123.\n* (1894). [https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/La_Civilisation_et_les_grands_fleuves_historiques_(de_Vog\u00fc\u00e9) \"La Civilisation et les Grands Fleuves Historiques,\"] ''Revue des Deux Mondes'', Vol. 125.\n* (1895). [https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Jean-Jacques_Rousseau_et_le_Cosmopolitisme_litt\u00e9raire \"Jean-Jacques Rousseau et le Cosmopolitisme Litt\u00e9raire,\"] ''Revue des Deux Mondes'', Vol. 130.\n\n'''Posthumous'''\n* (1911). [https://archive.org/stream/sousleslauriers00voguoft#page/n7/mode/2up ''Sous les Lauriers; \u00c9loges Acad\u00e9miques.'']\n* (1932). ''Journal du Vicomte Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9: Paris, Saint-P\u00e9tersbourg 1877-1883.''\n\n'''Translated into English'''\n* (1889). [http://www.unz.org/Pub/Harpers-1889may-00833 \"Social Life in Russia,\"] [http://www.unz.org/Pub/Harpers-1889jun-00003 Part II], ''The Harper's Monthly.''\n* (1887). [https://archive.org/stream/russiannovelists00voguoft#page/n3/mode/2up ''The Russian Novelists.'']\n** (1916). [https://archive.org/stream/russiannovel00sawygoog#page/n9/mode/2up ''The Russian Novel.'']\n* (1890). [http://www.unz.org/Pub/Harpers-1890jun-00026 \"Through the Caucasus,\"] ''The Harper's Monthly.''\n* (1891). ''The Tsar and his People: or, Social Life in Russia.''\n** [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=yale.39002067816299;view=1up;seq=13 \"Social Life in Russia,\"] pp.&nbsp;1\u201398.\n** [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=yale.39002067816299;view=1up;seq=115 \"Through the Caucasus,\"] pp.&nbsp;101\u2013147.\n* (1892). [http://www.unz.org/Pub/Harpers-1892jan-00234 \"The Neo-Christian Movement in France,\"] ''The Harper's Monthly.''\n* (1895). ''Russian Portraits.''\n* (1897). [http://www.unz.org/Pub/Forum-1897jan-00513 \"Leo XIII,\"] ''The Forum.''\n* (1904). ''The Master of the Sea.''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{Catholic|wstitle=Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior, Vicomte de Vog\u00fc\u00e9}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Blaze de Bury, Yetta (1898). [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b3130536;view=1up;seq=147 \"Eug\u00e8ne-Melchior de Vog\u00fc\u00e9.\"] In: ''French Literature of Today.'' Boston and New York: Houghton, Mifflin & Company, pp.&nbsp;133\u2013155.\n* [[\u00c9douard Rod|Rod, \u00c9douard]] (1892). [