{"title_page": "Buick Regal", "text_new": "{{short description|Mid-sized car model}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Buick Regal\n| image = Buick Regal 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = 2018 Buick Regal\n| manufacturer = [[Buick]] ([[General Motors]])\n| aka = [[Opel Insignia]] (Europe)<br />[[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] Insignia (United Kingdom)<br />[[Holden Commodore (ZB)]] (Australia, New Zealand)\n| model_years = '''North America'''<br />1973\u20132004<br />2011\u2013present<!--Until production has stopped, production dates should be \"present\" - DO NOT change to \"2020\"--><br />'''China'''<br />1999\u2013present\n| class = [[Mid-size|Mid-size car]] ([[D-segment|D]]) (1973-1987, 2009-present)<br />[[Mid-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[E-segment|E]]) (1988-2004)\n| layout = [[FR layout]] (1973\u20131987)<br />[[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|FF layout]] (1988\u2013present)<br />[[F4 layout]] (2008\u20132020)\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = [[Buick Skylark#1968\u20131972|Buick Skylark]] (1972)\n| successor = [[Buick LaCrosse]] (for Regal, 1988\u20132004)\n}}\nThe '''Buick Regal''' is an upscale [[mid-size]]d [[car|automobile]] that was first introduced by [[Buick]] for the 1973 model year. The model was originally positioned as a [[personal luxury car]], and typically offered in both [[Coup\u00e9|coupe]] and [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] forms until 1997, when the Regal became sedan-only due to the decline of the personal luxury coupe market. For certain model years between 1973 and 2004, the Regal shared bodies and powertrains with the similar [[Buick Century]], although the Regal was positioned as a more upmarket vehicle.\n\nThe Regal was discontinued in the North American market in 2004, being succeeded by the [[Buick LaCrosse]]. In 2008, a new version of the Regal was introduced for the Chinese market, which is a [[Rebadging|badge engineered]] version of the [[Opel Insignia]]. The new Regal was introduced to the North American market in 2011, positioned as a mid-size vehicle. A new model was introduced for 2018, which is offered in a [[liftback]] sedan and a \"TourX\" [[station wagon]] version.  GM plans to discontinue the Regal in the North American market after the 2020 model year, making Buick exclusively an SUV/CUV marque there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2019/12/04/buick-regal-discontinued-gm-general-motors/2607182001/|title=General Motors kills the Buick Regal: GM continues to cut passenger cars|last=Bomey|first=Nathan|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/386005/buick-regal-dead-after-2020my/|title=Buick Regal Dead After 2020MY Because Customers Want Crossovers|work=[[Motorsport Network|Motor1.com]]|last=Padeanu|first=Adrian|date=4 December 2019|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30120611/buick-regal-dead/|title=Buick Regal Is Dead, Leaving Buick with an All-SUV Lineup|work=[[Car and Driver]]|last=Capparella|first=Joey|date=4 December 2019|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== First generation (1973) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = First generation\n| image          = File:1974 Buick Regal (26756596603).jpg\n| caption        = 1974 Buick Regal coupe\n| aka              = Buick Century Regal\n| model_years    = 1973\u20131977\n| assembly       = {{unbulleted list|United States: [[Flint, Michigan]] ([[Buick City]])|[[Framingham, Massachusetts]] ([[Framingham Assembly]])|[[Fremont, California]] ([[Fremont Assembly]])|[[Lakewood Heights, Atlanta|Lakewood Heights, Georgia]] ([[Lakewood Assembly]])}}\n| engine         = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Buick V6 engine#231|Buick]]'' [[V6 engine|V6]] (gasoline)|{{convert|350|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Buick V8 engine#350|Buick]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]] (gasoline)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|455|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Buick V8 engine#455|Buick]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]] (gasoline)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| transmission   = {{unbulleted list|3-speed ''[[Turbo-Hydramatic]] [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM350|350]]'' automatic<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|3-speed ''[[Turbo-Hydramatic]] [[Turbo-Hydramatic#Super Turbine 400 .2F THM400 .2F THM375 .2F 3L80 .2F 3L80HD|400]]'' automatic<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| wheelbase      = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|112|in|mm|abbr=on}} (coupe)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|116|in|mm|abbr=on}} (sedan)<ref name=\"carbrochure\">{{cite web|author=Dusan Ristic-Petrovic |url=http://oldcarbrochures.com/new/021110/1974%20Buick%20Century/1974%20Buick%20Century-06.html |title=File: 1974 Buick Century/1974 Buick Century-06 |publisher=Oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-08}}</ref>}}\n| length         = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|212|in|mm|abbr=on}} (coupe)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|216|in|mm|abbr=on}} (sedan)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| height        = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|53.3|in|mm|abbr=on}} (coupe)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|54.1|in|mm|abbr=on}} (sedan)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| body_style     = 2-door [[coupe]]<br />4-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| related        = {{unbulleted list|[[Buick Century#1973.E2.80.931977|Buick Century]]|[[Chevrolet El Camino#Fourth generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Chevrolet El Camino]]|[[Chevrolet Chevelle#Third generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Chevrolet Malibu]]|[[Chevrolet Monte Carlo#Second generation|Chevrolet Monte Carlo]]|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass#Fourth Generation - 1973.E2.80.931977|Oldsmobile Cutlass]]|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme#Third generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]]|[[Pontiac Grand Am#1973.E2.80.931975|Pontiac Grand Am]]|[[Pontiac Grand Prix#Third generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Pontiac Grand Prix]]}}\n| platform       = [[GM A platform (RWD)|A-body]]\n| layout         = [[FR layout]]\n| sp             = us\n}}\n\n[[File:Nona6.jpg|thumb|left|1973 Buick Regal coupe]]\n[[File:Buick-Regal-(A-body)-Vilnius-Lithuania-front.jpg|thumb|left|1976 Buick Regal sedan]]\n[[File:Buick-Regal-(A-body)-Vilnius-Lithuania-back.jpg|thumb|left|1976 Buick Regal sedan]]\n\n[[Buick]] had been the first GM division to bring a [[personal luxury car]] to market with its 1963 [[Buick Riviera|Riviera]], but was otherwise slow to react to the developing lower-priced mid-size personal luxury market, which [[Pontiac]] created with the 1969 [[Pontiac Grand Prix|Grand Prix]] and [[Chevrolet]] with the [[Chevrolet Monte Carlo|Monte Carlo]] the following year, 1970. At the same time, [[Oldsmobile]] added a formal notchback coup\u00e9 to its intermediate line, the [[Cutlass Supreme]], in 1970 and that model soon became Olds' best selling intermediate. Buick did not get its own personal luxury coupe until the GM intermediates were redesigned in 1973, the so-called \"Colonnade\" cars that eliminated hardtop models completely. In a curious name swap, the Skylark name was dropped from Buick's intermediate line and instead the Century nameplate, last used in the 1950s, was revived for them.\n\nA highly trimmed, two-door [[coupe]], the first Regal, officially marketed as the \"Century Regal Colonnade Hardtop coupe\", shared its front and rear styling with its Century parent with distinctions amounting to differing grilles and taillight lenses. The Regal shared the same \"Colonnade\" [[Hardtop|pillared hardtop]] roofline (a [[hardtop]] with [[Pillar (car)|B-pillars (center pillars)]] but frameless doors unlike a sedan body) and greenhouse (window area) with the Grand Prix, Monte Carlo, and Cutlass Supreme as well as the lower-priced Buick Century Luxus coupe. Like its corporate cousins, the Regal (and Luxus) featured the newly fashionable opera windows, which were small fixed rear-side windows surrounded by sheetmetal, instead of the traditional roll-down windows.\n\nFor the first [[model year]] in 1973, the Regal nameplate was only used for Buick's version of the GM intermediate [[personal luxury car|personal luxury]] [[coupe]], but the following year gained a [[sedan (car)|sedan]] companion (there was no Regal [[station wagon]]).\n\nRegal interiors were generally more luxurious than lesser Century models with woodgrain trim on [[dashboard]] and [[door panel]]s, along with door-pull straps and [[bench seat]]s with center [[armrest]]s with cloth, velour, or vinyl upholstery. Optionally available throughout the run was a 60/40 split bench seat with [[armrest]]. For 1976 and 1977, the Regal [[coup\u00e9|coupe]] was available with the S/R option that included reclining bucket seats with corduroy upholstery.\n\nThe model lasted five years with minimal changes, although there was a fairly substantial facelift in coupes for 1976 (sedans retained their original 1973 sheetmetal through 1977), which incorporated the recently-legalized rectangular headlights (horizontally mounted on coupes, and vertically on [[sedan (car)|sedan]]s\u2014much like the mid-1960s Pontiacs). The Regal coupe sold reasonably well, although it lagged behind the Monte Carlo and Cutlass Supreme which had become the best-selling cars in America by 1976.\n\nThe Regal was most commonly powered by [[Buick V8 engine#350|Buick's {{convert|350|cuin|L|abbr=on}} V8]], which was standard equipment on all models for 1973 and 1974, and optional on coupes but standard on sedans from 1975 to 1977, and the larger [[Buick V8 engine#455|{{convert|455|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} V8]] was optional for 1973 and 1974 models only. Starting in 1975, Regal coupes came standard with Buick's resurrected {{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[V6 engine]] previously offered on the 1964\u20131967 [[Buick Skylark|Skylark]]; the engine's tooling had been sold to [[Kaiser Motors]] for use in [[Jeep]] models (Kaiser was purchased by American Motors in 1970 and Jeep became an AMC division) and sold back to GM by AMC in 1974. For 1975 and 1976, the Century and Regal were the only mid-sized cars in America to offer V6 engines. The bolt pattern for this vehicle is 5\u00d7{{convert|4+3/4|in|mm|1}}.\n\nThe Century designation was quietly dropped from the Regal for 1975.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Second generation (1978) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Second generation\n| image = '87 Buick Regal Grand National (Auto classique A&W Ch\u00e2teauguay '12).JPG\n| caption = 1987 Buick Regal Grand National\n| model_years = 1978\u20131987\n| layout = [[FR layout]]\n| assembly = United States: {{ubl\n|[[Flint, Michigan]]\n|[[Lakewood Heights, Atlanta|Lakewood Heights, Georgia]]\n|[[Arlington, Texas]]\n|[[Framingham, Massachusetts]]\n|[[Fremont, California]]\n|[[Pontiac, Michigan]]\n|[[Kansas City, Missouri]] (Leeds)\n}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|108|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| related = {{ubl\n|[[Buick Century]]\n|[[Chevrolet El Camino]]\n|[[Chevrolet Malibu]]\n|[[Chevrolet Monte Carlo]]\n|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass]]\n|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]]\n|[[Pontiac Bonneville]]\n|[[Pontiac Grand Am]]\n|[[Pontiac Grand Prix]]\n|[[Pontiac Le Mans]]\n}}\n| engine = {{ubl\n|{{convert|196|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#3.2|Buick V6]]\n|{{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#LD5|Buick V6]]\n|{{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#LD5|Buick V6]] [[Turbocharger|Turbocharged]]\n|{{convert|252|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#4.1|Buick V6]]\n|{{convert|260|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Oldsmobile Diesel engine|Oldsmobile Diesel]] [[V6 engine|V6]]\n|{{convert|265|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Pontiac V8 engine#265|Pontiac V8]]\n|{{convert|301|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Pontiac V8 engine#301|Pontiac V8]]\n|{{convert|305|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Chevrolet Small-Block engine#305|Chevrolet]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n|{{convert|307|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Oldsmobile V8 engine#307|Oldsmobile V8]]\n|{{convert|350|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Oldsmobile Diesel engine|Oldsmobile Diesel]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n| transmission = {{ubl\n|3-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]\n|3-speed [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM200|THM200]] [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n|4-speed [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM200-4R|THM200-4R]] automatic\n}}\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]<br />4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br />5-door [[station wagon]]\n| platform = [[GM A platform (RWD)|A-body]] (1978\u20131981)<br />[[GM G platform (RWD)|G-body]] (1981\u20131987)\n| sp = us\n}}\n\nA downsized Regal appeared for the 1978 model year with Buick's new {{convert|196|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[V6 engine]] as standard equipment and a revised version of the venerable {{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} V6 as an option (which became standard for 1980). Initially, a three-speed [[manual transmission]] was standard but this was later replaced by an automatic. At the time of introduction, Regals were available exclusively as [[coup\u00e9]]s with the [[Buick Century|Century]] nameplate applied to bread-and-butter sedans and [[station wagon]]s.<ref name=\"buick\">{{Cite book | ref = SCBuick | title = Standard Catalog of Buick, 1903-2004 | edition = 3 | first = John | last = Gunnell | publisher = Krause Publications, Inc. | location = Iola, WI | page = 182 | date = 2004 | isbn = 0-87349-760-0 }}</ref> In January 1982 the Century was replaced by an all-new car on the [[front-wheel drive]] [[GM A platform (1982)|A platform]], which meant that the Regal gained a four-door sedan and five-door station wagon - essentially facelifted and [[Badge|rebadged]] versions of the previous year's [[rear-wheel drive]] Century. It was the first time the name appeared on a full model lineup. The wagon was discontinued after 1983, and the sedan dropped from the lineup the next year.<ref name=stdB>[[#SCBuick|Gunnell]], pp. 218, 224</ref> This generation Regal lasted ten years. The base model was equipped with softer-riding luxury [[Suspension (vehicle)|suspension]], and did not offer a manual transmission in later years.\n\n[[File:Buick Regal -- 08-14-2009.jpg|thumb|left|1978\u20131979 Buick Regal]]\n[[File:Regal A-Body.JPG|thumb|left|1980 Buick Regal]]\n[[File:1982 Buick Regal Wagon two-tone green, front right.jpg|thumb|left|1982 Buick Regal Estate Wagon]]\n[[File:Buick Regal G-Body.jpg|thumb|left|1982\u20131987 Buick Regal]]\n\nThe 1978 Regal could be equipped with a {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} [[Turbocharged]] V6 engine with [[automatic transmission]], and was known as a Regal Sport Coupe. Turbo versions were offered with either a two- or a four-barrel [[carburetor]]. The [[Buick LeSabre]] was also available with the turbocharged engine. The only other turbocharged cars available in the U.S. market in 1978 were imports from [[Mercedes-Benz]], [[Porsche 930|Porsche]] and [[Saab Automobile|Saab]]. The Regal Sport Coupe also included a firm [[Car handling|handling]] suspension with larger tires and sport wheels.  Bucket seats and a center console with a T-shifter were also available.\n\nA major facelift for 1981 gave the Regal a much more aerodynamic profile, helping make it possible for the car to compete on the [[NASCAR]] racing circuit. The sloping [[Hood (car)|hood]] and nose of the car made it the favorite of several NASCAR teams. [[Richard Petty]] drove one to victory in the [[1981 Daytona 500]], and the car won a majority of the 1981 and 1982 seasons races and won the NASCAR manufacturers title in 1981 and 1982.\n\n[[V8 engine|V8]]s for street use were still available, but had shrunk to {{convert|265|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} (1980 and 1981 only, [[Pontiac]] built), and the V6 was rapidly gaining popularity. From 1986 to 1987, the [[Oldsmobile V8 engine#307|{{convert|307|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8]] was available as an option. The {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} 2-bbl V6 was standard. The [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM200-4R|200-4R]] [[Overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]] [[Transmission (mechanics)|transmission]] was an option with either engine.\n\nFor 1980, the Regal was offered in a special '''Somerset Limited Edition''' [[Trim level (automobile)|trim]] which featured unique tan and dark blue designer exterior paint, wire wheel covers, sport [[Wing mirror|mirrors]], and chrome Somerset badging. The interior had tan and blue plush [[velour]] [[Upholstery#Automobile upholstery|upholstery]], brushed [[Chrome plating#Automotive use|chrome]] trim, and additional Somerset badging. A Somerset Limited Edition model was also offered on the restyled 1981 Regal. It had unique dark sandstone and camel exterior paint, sport mirrors, and turbine wheels. The interior plush velour upholstery was camel with dark brown piping.\n\n=== Grand National, Turbo-T, T-Type, and GNX ===\nIn February 1982, the Regal Grand National debuted, which was named for the [[NASCAR Sprint Cup Series|NASCAR Winston Cup Grand National Series]] (the \"Grand National\" term was part of the Cup series nomenclature until 1986).<ref>http://legendarydreamcargarage.com/dreamcargarage/539</ref> Buick had won the Manufacturers Cup in 1981 and 1982, and wanted to capitalize on its success: \"What wins on Sunday, sells on Monday\". These 1982 cars were not painted black, which may confuse those not familiar with them. All started out as charcoal gray Regals that were shipped off to a subcontractor for finishing.\n\nOriginally intended for a run of 100 units, Cars and Concepts of [[Brighton, Michigan]], retrofitted 215 Regals with the GN package. Most obvious was the light silver gray firemist paint added to each side. Red [[Pinstriping#Automobiles|pinstripes]] and billboard shadow lettering proclaiming \"Buick\" were applied. The wheel opening moldings and [[rocker panel]] moldings were blacked out using black vinyl tape. Finally, a front air dam and [[rear spoiler]] were installed. On the inside, special \"Lear-Siegler\" seats were installed. These seats are fully adjustable and were covered with silver brandon cloth with black vinyl inserts. The front seat had Buick's \"6\" emblem embroidered onto them. Also, a special clock delete plate was added to the [[Dashboard|instrument panel]] which contained the yellow and orange \"6\" logo and the words \"Grand National Buick Motor Division\".)\n\nThe 1982 GN came with a [[naturally aspirated]] {{convert|252|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V6 engine with {{convert|125|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|205|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]] at 2000&nbsp;rpm. Of the 215 Regal Grand Nationals produced in 1982, at least 35 were based on the Buick Regal Sport coupe package with the turbocharged {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} V6 engine with {{convert|175|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|275|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2600&nbsp;rpm. There were only 2022 Sport coupes produced in 1982, and the number of cars with both the GN and Sport coupe packages is estimated to be fewer than 50.\n\nFor 1983, there was no Grand National. The Sport coupe model was renamed the [[T-Type]]; 3,732 were produced ({{convert|190|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 1600&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2400&nbsp;rpm). The T-Type had been used on other Buicks, starting with the [[Buick Riviera|Riviera]] in 1981 (in 1979 and 1980, it was the S Type). The 1983 Regal T-Type featured tube [[Exhaust manifold|headers]], Hydro-Boost II [[brake]]s, 200-4R 4-speed overdrive trans and 3.42 [[rear axle]] (7.5\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autotraderclassics.com/car-article/Future+Collectible%3A+1986+Buick+Grand+National*T_Type-66683.xhtml |title=Buick Grand National Buyer's Guide |publisher=Autotraderclassics.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-10}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Buick T-Type (2669441886).jpg|thumb|Buick Regal T-Type]]\n\nFor 1984, the Grand National returned, now in all black paint. The [[turbocharged]] {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} became standard and was refined with [[sequential fuel injection]], [[distributor]]-less computer controlled [[Ignition system|ignition]], and boasted {{convert|200|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4400&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|300|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2400&nbsp;rpm. Only 5,204 turbo Regals were produced that year, only 2,000 of which were Grand Nationals. Because this was the first year production of the computer controlled sequential fuel injection and distributor-less ignition, this is often considered the year and model that started the development of the legendary [[intercooled]] Grand Nationals. The performance of this package was well ahead of its time and the \"little V6\" easily kept up with the bigger V8s. [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] performance was listed at 15.9 seconds at stock boost levels of {{convert|10|psi|bar|abbr=on}}, while for the same year, the [[Chevrolet Camaro (third generation)|Chevrolet Camaro]] V6 was listed at 17.0 and the [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|Chevrolet Corvette]] at 15.2 seconds.<ref name=cd_corvette>\n{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/1984-chevrolet-corvette-c4-archived-road-test\n|title=1984 Corvette (C4) \n|date=1983-03-01\n|publisher=Car and Driver\n}}</ref> Soon, performance enthusiasts determined the modifications that worked and the Grand Nationals easily broke into the 13-second territory. All Grand Nationals had the [[Lear Siegler]]-made cloth/leather interior which was only available for this year. An estimated 200 of the 1984 Grand Nationals were produced with the T-Top option which makes these the rarest of the Grand Nationals.\n\nFor 1986, a modified engine design with air-air intercooling boosted the performance even further to a specified {{convert|235|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|330|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2400&nbsp;rpm. The Grand Nationals (quantity 5,512) and T-Types (quantity 2,384) were both produced in 1986. For 1987, performance reached {{convert|245|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|355|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. Buick dropped the T-Type package for Regal for 1987 models and opted for a \"T\" sport package instead. There were only 7,896 turbo Regals produced in 1986. In 1987, when turbo Regals reached their peak in popularity, a total of 27,590 turbo Regals were produced through December, with those models produced between September and December of that year window stickered as \"1987\u00bd Buick Grand National\" vehicles.\n\n[[File:WO2T.jpg|thumb|1987 Regal turbo-T Limited with rare blackout trim package]]\n\nFor 1987, a lightweight WE4 (turbo T) option was offered. Only 1,547 of this variant were produced. The differences between a WE4 and the Grand National were the interior trim package, wheels, exterior badging, aluminum bumper supports, and aluminum rear [[drum brake]]s as opposed to the Grand National's cast iron, making the WE4 a lighter and faster car. The rear spoiler was only available as a dealer installed option. Nineteen eighty-seven was the only year that the LC2 turbo option was available on any Regal, making it possible to even see a Limited with a vinyl [[Landau (automobile)|landau roof]] and a [[power bulge]] turbo hood. Turbo Regal Limiteds were one of the rarest models of turbo Regals produced second only to the GNX at 1,035 turbo Limiteds. Turbo Regal Limiteds could be ordered with many options with most having chrome external trim but for $35 could have been built with the full black-out trim option making them extremely rare. Limiteds were treated to a very luxurious interior with plush carpeting and optional bench pillow seats and a [[Gear stick|column shift]]. The 1987 model would be the end of the manufacture of the [[Rear wheel drive|RWD]] \"G-Body\" Regal, but [[General Motors|GM]] had to extend the build of the Grand National to meet customer demand into December.\n[[File:Buick GNX (20206519195).jpg|thumb|Buick Regal GNX]]\n[[File:Buick GNX (20180268696).jpg|thumb|Buick Regal GNX]]\nFor the final year, 1987, Buick introduced the limited production GNX, for \"Grand National Experimental\", at $29,900. Made in partnership with [[Linamar|McLaren Performance Technologies]]/[[American Specialty Cars|ASC]], Buick produced only 547 GNs with the interior trim package, that were then sent off to [[Linamar|McLaren]] and upgraded into the Buick GNX. Buick underrated the GNX at {{Convert|276|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4400&nbsp;rpm and a very substantial {{convert|360|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3000&nbsp;rpm of [[Torque#Machine torque|torque]],<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=100661\n|title=1987 Buick Regal GNX\n|website=Carfolio.com\n|accessdate=2018-09-23\n|date=2013-02-28}}</ref> although actual output is {{convert|300|bhp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|420|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"GNXPerf\">{{cite web|url=http://home.att.net/~buickGNX/GNX/perf.htm |title=GNX Performance |work=BuickGNX.com |accessdate=2007-07-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630104145/http://home.att.net/~buickGNX/GNX/perf.htm |archivedate=June 30, 2007 }}</ref> This was created to be the \"Grand National to end all Grand Nationals.\" Changes made included a special [[Garrett AiResearch]] T-3 [[turbocharger]] with a ceramic-impeller blowing through a more efficient and significantly larger capacity [[intercooler]] with a \"Cermatel (ceramic-aluminum) coated\" pipe connecting the intercooler to the engine. A GNX specific E-EPROM, low-restriction exhaust with dual [[muffler]]s, reprogrammed turbo Hydramatic 200-4R transmission with a custom [[torque converter]] and transmission cooler, and unique [[Differential (mechanical device)|differential]] cover/[[Panhard]] bar included more of the performance modifications. Exterior styling changes include vents located on each front fender, 16&nbsp;inch black mesh style wheels with VR-speed rated tires, and deletion of the hood and fender emblems. The interior changes of the GNX included a serial number on the dash plaque and a revised instrument cluster providing [[Stewart-Warner]] [[Analog device|analog gauges]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Popular Mechanics |date=March 1987 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HOMDAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> including an analog turbo [[boost gauge]]. Performance was measured faster than the [[Ferrari F40]] and the [[Porsche 930]] with a [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] time of 12.7 seconds at {{Convert|113.1|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} (0.3 and 0.8 seconds quicker, 2.9 and {{convert|13.3|mph|0|abbr=on}} faster) and a 0-{{convert|60|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} time of 4.6 seconds (0.4 and 0.3 seconds quicker, respectively).<ref>[http://imgur.com/gallery/uzXOy], ''MotorTrend'', accessed Aug 11, 2016.</ref>\nGNX #001 is the 1986 prototype currently owned by Buick and sometimes makes appearances at car shows around the US. The GNX used a unique [[torque arm]] that was mounted to a special, GNX only, rear differential cover, for increased [[Traction (engineering)|traction]]. The torque arm rear suspension alters the suspension geometry, making the body lift while planting the rear tires down, resulting in increased traction.\n\nThe stealthy appearance of the all-black GNX and Grand National (and the resemblance of its grill to his helmet's mouthpiece), coupled with the fact that the Grand National was initially released during the popularity of ''[[Star Wars]]'' movies, earned it the title \"[[Darth Vader]]'s Car\". [[Car and Driver]] covered the GNX model's introduction with the headline \"Lord Vader, your car is ready.\"  Due to the turbocharged six cylinder engine, the Buick make, and the black paint Grand Nationals were sometimes referred to as the \"Dark Side\". The \"Dark Side\" contrasted with the more common V8 [[Ford Mustang (third generation)|Mustangs]] and Camaros that were popular at the time.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Third generation (1988) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Third generation\n| image = Buick gray.jpg\n| caption = 1988\u20131989 Buick Regal Limited coupe\n| model_years = 1988&ndash;1996\n| production = 1987\u2013October 1996<ref>https://www.cars.com/reviews/chicagotribunecoms-view-1420689074485/</ref>\n| transmission = 4-speed automatic<br />1988\u201392: [[GM 4T60 transmission|4T60]]<br />1993\u201396: [[GM 4T60-E transmission|4T60-E]]\n| engine = 2.8 L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Transverse|X]]'' [[V6]]<br />3.1 L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation II|X]]'' [[V6]]<br />3.8 L ''[[Buick V6 engine#3800 V6|Buick]]'' [[V6]]\n| assembly = [[Oshawa, Ontario]], Canada ([[GM Canada]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coupe]]<br />4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|107.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = 1988\u201389 2dr: {{convert|192.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1990\u201391 2dr: {{convert|191.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1992\u201394 2dr: {{convert|193.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1995\u201396 2dr: {{convert|193.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1990\u201391 4dr: {{convert|194.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1992\u201394 Custom & GS 4dr: {{convert|194.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1992\u201394 Limited 4dr: {{convert|196|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1995 4dr: {{convert|193.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1996 4dr: {{convert|194.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|72.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = Sedan: {{convert|54.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />Coupe: {{convert|53|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| related = [[Chevrolet Lumina#First generation .281990.E2.80.931994.29|Chevrolet Lumina]]<br />[[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme#Fifth generation .281988.E2.80.931997.29|Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]]<br />[[Pontiac Grand Prix#Fifth generation .281988.E2.80.931996.29|Pontiac Grand Prix]]\n| platform = [[GM W platform|W-body]]\n| layout = [[FF layout]]\n| designer = \n| sp = us\n}}\n\n[[File:'88-'89 Buick Regal (Orange Julep).JPG|thumb|left|1988\u20131989 Buick Regal GS coupe]]\n[[File:Buick Regal 2 -- 10-30-2009.jpg|thumb|left|1990\u20131994 Buick Regal GS sedan]]\n[[File:1991 Buick Regal Limited.jpg|thumb|left|1991 Buick Regal Limited coupe]]\n[[File:Buick Regal coupe.jpg|thumb|left|1995\u20131996 Buick Regal coupe]]\n[[File:95-96 Buick Regal.jpg|thumb|left|1996 Buick Regal sedan]]\n\nA new Regal appeared in October 1987 on the [[GM W platform]] as the first vehicle on that platform;<ref>http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1987-08-30-8703050938-story.html</ref> this generation ran with few changes for nine years. Though the new Regal returned to Buick's original concept in being offered only as a coupe and in being aimed once again squarely at the personal luxury buyer, it departed from tradition in being the first front-wheel drive model, and in having no serious performance option or edition. Neither a [[V8 engine|V8]] engine nor a turbocharged [[V6]] was offered; the only engine available for 1988 was the Chevrolet 2.8&nbsp;L V6, producing {{convert|125|hp|abbr=on}}.\n\nFrom 1990, owing to the declining personal luxury car market, the Regal was again offered as a four-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] (as were the Cutlass Supreme and Grand Prix the same year, the latter offered as a sedan for the first time).\n\nThe Regal was initially offered in base ''Custom'' and upscale ''Limited'' trim lines. For 1989, the ''[[Buick Gran Sport#Regal GS / Regal Gran Sport|Gran Sport]]'' trim line was added, featuring aluminum wheels, body side cladding and a console mounted shifter attached to the 4-speed automatic. For 1990, the Regal gained the option of the Buick 3.8&nbsp;L V6. The 3800 V6 was unique to the Regal, differentiating it from the mechanically similar [[Chevrolet Lumina]], [[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]] and [[Pontiac Grand Prix]]. Anti-lock brakes were made standard on all but the base ''Custom'' cars from 1992, and the grille was redesigned again for 1993. Along with the new look came an electronically controlled [[automatic transmission]] and [[Buick LeSabre|LeSabre]]-like rear lights and bumper. For 1993, a driver's side [[airbag]] was added, along with standard [[Anti-lock braking system|ABS]] on all models, standard power windows, and {{convert|20|hp|0|abbr=on}} more in the base engine due to a revised intake manifold and cylinder head. The ''Limited'' coupe was deleted; only the ''Custom'' and ''Gran Sport (GS)'' coupes remained. Dual airbags were new for 1995 along with a new interior.\n\nFor 1996, the larger {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} V6 engine became the ''3800 Series II'' and gained {{convert|35|hp|0|abbr=on}}. {{citation needed span|Although 1996 was the last model year of this model, sales continued into 1997 as the replacement model was late (arriving in January 1997).|date=October 2018}}\n\n=== Engines ===\n* 1988\u20131989 2.8&nbsp;L (170&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation II|Chevrolet LB6]] [[MPFI|MFI]] [[V6]], {{Convert|125|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|160|lbft|0|abbr=on}}\n* 1989\u20131993 3.1&nbsp;L (191&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation II|Chevrolet LH0]] MFI V6, {{Convert|140|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|180|lbft|0|abbr=on}}\n* 1994\u20131996 3.1&nbsp;L (191&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation III|Chevrolet L82]] SFI V6, {{Convert|160|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|185|lbft|Nm|abbr=on}}\n* 1990\u20131995 3.8&nbsp;L (231&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[L27 Naturally Aspirated|Buick L27]] V6, {{Convert|170|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|220|lbft|0|abbr=on}}\n* 1996 3.8&nbsp;L (231&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[Buick V6 engine#L36 Naturally Aspirated|Buick L36]] V6, {{Convert|200|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|225|lbft|Nm|abbr=on}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n== {{anchor|Fourth}} Fourth generation (1997) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Fourth generation\n| image = Buick Regal GSE.jpg\n| caption = Buick Regal (US)\n| aka = Chevrolet Lumina (Philippines)\n| production = {{ubl | 1996\u20132004 | China: 1999&ndash;2008 || Philippines: 2005&ndash;2006 }}\n| model_years = North America: 1997&ndash;2004\n| assembly = {{unbulleted list|Canada: [[Oshawa, Ontario]], [[GM Canada]]|China: [[Shanghai]], [[Shanghai GM]]}}\n| predecessor = \n| successor = [[Buick LaCrosse]]\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| layout = [[FF layout]]\n| platform = [[GM W platform|W-body 2nd Gen]]\n| engine = 2.0 L ''[[Family II engine#L34|L34]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (China)<br />2.5&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#China|LB8]]'' [[V6 engine|V6]] (China)<br />3.0&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LW9|LW9]]'' [[V6 engine|V6]] (China)<br />3.8 L [[Buick V6 engine#Series II|3800 Series II]] [[V6]]\n| transmission = 5-speed manual (China, 2.0 L only) <br /> 4-speed [[GM 4T60-E transmission#4T60-E|4T60-E]] automatic <br /> 4-speed [[GM 4T60-E transmission#4T65-E|4T65-E]] automatic <br /> 4-speed [[GM 4T60-E transmission#4T65-E|4T65-E HD]] automatic\n| wheelbase = {{convert|109.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|196.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|72.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|56.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = \n| related = {{unbulleted list |[[Buick Century#1997.E2.80.932005|Buick Century]]|[[Chevrolet Impala#Eighth|Chevrolet Impala]]|[[Chevrolet Monte Carlo#Sixth|Chevrolet Monte Carlo]]|[[Oldsmobile Intrigue]]|[[Pontiac Grand Prix#Sixth generation .281997.E2.80.932003.29|Pontiac Grand Prix]]}}\n| designer = Wayne Cherry<br />Wayne Kady (1993)\n| sp = us\n}}\n{{see also|Buick Century#1997\u20132005|l1=Buick Century \u00a7 1997\u20132005}}\n\n[[File:Buick Regal.jpg|thumb|left|1997\u20132004 Buick Regal sedan]]\n\nFor the 1997 model year, the Century and Regal once again rode upon the same platform; the revised [[GM W platform|W platform]] that was shared with the [[Oldsmobile Intrigue]], the [[Pontiac Grand Prix]], the [[Chevrolet Lumina]] and [[Chevrolet Monte Carlo]].<ref>https://adage.com/article/news/buick-s-regal-read-costly-web-launch/263/</ref> The Regal coupe was discontinued.\n\nDifferences between the Regal and Century were mostly cosmetic. As the upmarket version, the Regal offered larger engines and fancier trim, and once again boasted a newer version of the 3.8&nbsp;L V6. While the Century was mainly a reliable, economy-minded car based upon the W-body, the Regal was fitted with many amenities, including heated leather seats (optional on the Century), a [[Monsoon speakers|Monsoon]] 8-speaker surround sound system, dual climate control, and expansive interior space. Few changes occurred during this version's seven-year run. It offered 5-passenger seating on all trim levels like the Pontiac Grand Prix and Oldsmobile Intrigue (formerly Cutlass Supreme), unlike their predecessors that had optional 6-passenger seating and the Buick Century (formerly built on the [[GM A platform|A platform]]) which had standard 6-passenger seating.\n\nThis period held the fastest Buick since the days of the 1991\u20131996 Roadmaster, the Buick Regal GS. This car was now [[supercharged]] instead of turbocharged, and produced {{convert|240|hp|abbr=on|0}} and {{convert|280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. When introduced in January 1997,<ref>http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1996-08-11-9608110276-story.html</ref> Buick advertised the Regal GS as \"The official car of the supercharged family\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LoghkBiMmQk</ref> Buick also released two other model types, the LSE and the GSE. The LSE stayed with the {{convert|200|hp|abbr=on|0}} engine with upgrades and the GSE stayed with the {{convert|240|hp|abbr=on|0}} supercharged engine with upgrades. Also, in 2000 Buick came out with a concept GSX that had an intercooled 3.8&nbsp;L, but was supercharged rather than turbocharged. It had {{convert|295.24|hp|abbr=on}}\n\nThe North American Regal was replaced in 2005 by the [[Buick LaCrosse]], also built on the W platform. The final 2004 Buick Regal rolled off the assembly line on June 1, 2004.<ref name=\"Wards05\">{{cite book |title=Ward's Automotive Yearbook 2005 |publisher=Ward's Communications, Inc |year=2005 |page=112}}</ref>\n\n=== Engines ===\n* 1997\u20132004 [[GM 3800 engine#L36|3.8]]&nbsp;L L36 Series II [[V6]]\n* 1997\u20132004 [[GM 3800 engine#L67|3.8]]&nbsp;L L67 Series II supercharged [[V6]]\n\n=== Regal LS and GS performance ===\n[[File:Regal l67.jpg|thumb|left|The 3800 Series II L67 Supercharged engine in a 1998 GS]]\n\nThe Regal LS from the factory had a 1/4 mile (\u2248400 m) elapsed time (ET) of 15.8 seconds and could do 0-60&nbsp;mph in under 8 seconds. The supercharged Regal GS had a 1/4 mile ET of 14.9 seconds, and acceleration to {{convert|60|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} took 6.7 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |author=Albee Digital Communications |url=http://www.albeedigital.com/supercoupe/articles/0-60_Quarter_Mile_Times/B_0-60times.html |title=\"B\" 0-60 and 1/4 mile times for Factory Stock Vehicles |publisher=Albeedigital.com |accessdate=2009-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410163805/http://www.albeedigital.com/supercoupe/articles/0-60_Quarter_Mile_Times/B_0-60times.html |archivedate=2013-04-10 }}</ref>  The Regal GS, equipped with the supercharged 3.8 liter V6 engine (L67) produced {{convert|240|hp|abbr=on|0}} & {{convert|280|lb\u00b7ft|N.m|abbr=on}} of torque. The Regal GS's PCM has programming that activates torque management to reduce wheel spin at launch. The Regal LS was EPA rated at 19/30 MPG city/freeway while the supercharged Regal GS was EPA rated at 18/27 MPG city/freeway.\n\n=== Regal LSX and GSX (SLP Performance) ===\n[[File:Buick_Regal_GSX.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal GSX]]\nIn the 2003 and 2004 model years, Buick, in collaboration with SLP Performance, came out with the Buick Regal GSX. They offered dealer-installed options and dealer supplied accessories for both LS and GS models. Like the GS Buicks that came before it, the SLP GSX came in three power train packages, referred to as stages. The Stage 1 package added 10 horsepower with the addition of a dual stainless steel cat-back exhaust system and free-flowing cold air induction system. If you opted for the Stage 2 package, a Hypertech Power Programmer with an SLP custom calibration tune was included with the Stage 1 components \u2014 good for an extra 20 horsepower. The range-topping Stage 3 package added a 3.5-inch smaller diameter supercharger pulley to crank up the boost. With an advertised 30 more horsepower than stock, the Stage 3 GSX was conservatively rated at {{convert|270|hp|abbr=on|0}} and {{convert|312|lbft|abbr=on|0}} of torque. Since the parts were available from SLP over the counter for many years, there have been quite a few Regal GS sedans that have been cloned into a GSX for both appearance and performance purposes. Though the model didn\u2019t officially debut until 2003, a licensed SLP dealer could perform the transformation on any Regal GS from 1997 to 2004. A true GSX can be verified from an SLP door jamb label with the correct part number for the kit.<ref>https://www.cheatsheet.com/automobiles/buick-regal-gsx-it-lives-up-to-its-performance-heritage.html/</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fabini.com/slp/slpbuickgsx.html |title=SLP Buick Regal GSX |work=Fabini's Auto Trim Co |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710215458/http://www.fabini.com/slp/slpbuickgsx.html |archivedate=2011-07-10 }}</ref>\n\n===Joseph Abboud Edition===\nFrom 2001 to 2004 Buick offered a [[Joseph Abboud]] appearance package on both the GS and LS models. This package included either a solid [[taupe]] or two-tone taupe/[[Chestnut (color)|chestnut]] leather seats, two-tone leather wrapped steering wheel, leather shifter handle and boot, 16\" aluminum wheels; and Joseph Abboud signature emblems on the front doors, floor mats, front seat head rests, and taillights.\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:Buick Regal CN 01 China 2012-06-16.jpg|thumb|left|1999\u20132008 Buick Regal front quarter (China)]]\n[[File:Buick Regal CN 02 China 2012-06-16.jpg|thumb|right|1999\u20132008 Buick Regal rear quarter (China)]]\nGeneral Motors and [[Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation]] (SAIC) established a joint venture in 1997 called [[Shanghai GM]], and had begun assembling the Buick Regal in [[Shanghai]], [[People's Republic of China|China]] in April 1999.<ref name=china_0>{{cite web |url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1995%2C_GM_Links_with_SAIC |title=1995, GM Links with SAIC |year=2011 |work=history.gmheritagecenter.com |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z3cvAY0i?url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1995,_GM_Links_with_SAIC# |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=GM signed a milestone agreement with China\u2019s Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation (SAIC) for a proposed automotive joint venture, a joint venture technical center, and several other projects in and around the city of Shanghai... |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=globalization>{{cite web |url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1982_-1999,_Globalization,_One_Company,_One_Team |title=1982 -1999, Globalization, One Company, One Team |year=2011 |work=history.gmheritagecenter.com |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z3Uy5pg2?url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1982_-1999,_Globalization,_One_Company,_One_Team# |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=Also in 1995, the company entered into a joint venture agreement with Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation (SAIC) in China, laying the foundation for unprecedented growth over the next few years. Four years later, the Buick Regal was being assembled in China for the Chinese market... |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1999,_Buick_is_Back_in_Shanghai |title=1999, Buick is Back in Shanghai |year=2011 |work=history.gmheritagecenter.com |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z3V6i6Em?url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1999,_Buick_is_Back_in_Shanghai# |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=The General Motors-SAIC joint venture plant in Shanghai began building Buick Regals for the Chinese market, marking the Buick brand\u2019s proud return to China. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Regal has sold well in the Chinese market as a large, relatively luxurious model, despite its high price, costing more than the North American version. The Chinese market Regal has different front- and rear-end styling compared to the North American version and different engines, including the 2.0&nbsp;L ''[[Family II engine#L34|L34]]'', the 2.5&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LB8|LB8]]'' V6 and the 3.0&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LW9|LW9]]'' V6. Gearbox choices were a 4-speed automatic for V6 models, while four-cylinder variants are paired with a 5-speed manual gearbox. V6 models had a set of black dashboard gauges, while the four-cylinder models had white dashboard gauges.  These models also had slightly different names: the entry-level model was the ''New Century'', with more upscale models carrying the ''GL'' and ''GLX'' names. Later, ''G'' and ''GS'' models were added. Production for this generation ended in November 2008 in China being replaced the Opel Insignia based Regal. The Chinese-built Regal was also sold in the Philippines from 2005 to 2008 as the Chevrolet Lumina, where it replaced the [[Opel Vectra]]. The 2.5 V6 was the only engine option.<ref>https://www.curbsideclassic.com/automotive-histories/obscure-rebadges-from-around-the-world-part-6/</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n== Fifth generation (2008) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Fifth generation\n| image = 2011 Buick Regal -- 07-04-2011.jpg\n| caption = 2011 Buick Regal CXL\n| aka = [[Opel Insignia]]<br />[[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] Insignia<br />[[Chevrolet]] Vectra<br />[[Holden]] Insignia\n| production = 2008\u20132017\n| model_years = China: 2009\u20132017<br /> North America: 2011\u20132017\n| assembly = [[People's Republic of China|China]]: November 2008\u20132017 ([[Shanghai General Motors]]) <br /> Germany: 2009\u2013February 2011 ([[Opel]] [[R\u00fcsselsheim]] Assembly)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoobserver.com/2011/09/sexy-opel-astra-gtc-could-be-next-new-buick.html|title=Sexy Opel Astra GTC Could Be Next New Buick|work=AutoObserver Sexy Opel Astra GTC Could Be Next New Buick}}</ref> <br /> Canada: [[Oshawa, Ontario]] February 2011\u20132017 ([[General Motors Canada]])\n| designer = Mark Adams (2006)<ref>https://www.motortrend.com/cars/buick/regal/2010/2010-buick-regal-drive/</ref> <br /> Malcolm Ward (2006)\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| platform = [[GM Epsilon II platform|Epsilon II]]\n| related = [[Buick LaCrosse]] <br /> [[Chevrolet Malibu]] <br /> [[Cadillac XTS]] <br /> [[Saab 9-5]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|FF layout]] / [[F4 layout]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list\n  |1.6 L ''[[GM Family 1 engine#Generation III|LLU]]'' [[Turbocharger|turbo]] [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (China Only)\n  |2.0 L ''LTD'' I4 (China Only)\n  |2.0 L ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LDK|LDK]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LHU|LHU]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' turbo I4\n  |2.4 L ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LE5|LE5]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LAF|LAF]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LEA|LEA]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LUK|LUK]]'' I4\n}}\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list |6-speed [[Hydra-Matic]] ''[[GM 6T40 transmission|6T40]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|6-speed [[Hydra-Matic]] ''[[GM 6T50 transmission|6T50]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|6-speed [[Hydra-Matic]] ''[[GM 6T70 transmission|6T70]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|6-speed [[Aisin Seiki Co.#Aisin AW|Aisin]] ''[[AWTF-80 SC|AF40]]'' automatic|6-speed [[Aisin]] ''[[GM F40|F40]]'' [[Manual transmission|manual]]}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|107.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|190.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|73.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|58.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{Convert|3600|lbs|abbr=on}} (2011 CXL) <br /> {{Convert|3671|lbs|abbr=on}} (2011 CXL Turbo)\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = [[Saturn Aura]]\n| successor = \n}}\n\n{{See also|Opel Insignia}}\n[[File:Buick (12645920815).jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal]]\nThe fifth-generation Buick Regal is a four-door, five-passenger, [[Mid-size car|midsized]] [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] with a [[FF layout|front engine, front-wheel drive]] layout.<ref name=EPA_midsize>{{cite web |url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/2008car1tablef.jsp?id=30075 |title=2011 Buick Regal |year=2011 |work=fueleconomy.gov |publisher=United States Environmental Protection Agency |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4Zdiz4X?url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/2008car1tablef.jsp?id=30075 |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=Size Class Midsize Cars |url-status=dead }}</ref> GM says that the Regal is helping General Motors attract new, younger customers to the Buick brand. According to GM published information, more than 41% of Regal buyers in the US are coming from non-General Motors brands, and more than 60% of CXL Turbo buyers are under the age of 55.<ref name=gm_pr_110128>{{cite press release |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Jan/0128_regalturbo |title=Buick Regal Turbo Attracting New Customers to Brand |date=2011-01-28 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4fIzo1V?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Jan/0128_regalturbo |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=More than 60 percent of Regal Turbo customers alone are younger than 55, according to Power Information Network data. Since its launch last spring, 41 percent of Regal\u2019s buyers have come from non-GM brands. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Development ===\nThe fifth generation Buick Regal rides on GM's [[GM Epsilon II platform|Epsilon II]] platform and is mostly identical to the [[Opel Insignia]]. It first went into production in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Germany, in 2008.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/index.html |title=2011 Buick Regal |first=Todd |last=Lassa |date=November 2009 |work=motortrend.com |publisher=MotorTrend Magazine, Source Interlink Media |page=1 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4ZEcVDR?url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/specs.html |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=...GM planned to make the Opel Insignia Saturn's second-generation Aura. |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=regal_insignia>{{cite web |url=http://paultan.org/2008/11/05/new-buick-regal-for-china-based-on-insignia/ |title=New Buick Regal for China based on Insignia |first=Paul |last=Tan |date=2008-11-05 |work=Paul Tan's Automotive News |publisher=Driven Media Sdn Bhd |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z2AQjmKK?url=http://paultan.org/2008/11/05/new-buick-regal-for-china-based-on-insignia/ |archivedate=2011-05-29 |accessdate=2011-05-29 |quote=The new Opel Insignia (badged as a Vauxhall in the UK) is now in China, badged as a Buick. The Insignia is wearing the Buick Regal badge... |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[Shanghai GM]] twin of the Insignia was introduced in China as Buick Regal in December, 2008 for the 2009 model year.\n\nGM originally planned to sell a modified version of the Opel Insignia in North America as the second generation [[Saturn Aura]], but changed strategy after deciding to discontinue the [[Saturn Corporation|Saturn]] brand.<ref name=an_110508>{{cite web |url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110518/OEM04/110519901/1266 |title=Buick will get rebadged, redesigned Astra, report says |first=Rick |last=Kranz |date=2011-05-18 |work=autonews.com |publisher=Crain Communications, Inc |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z563fWtM?url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20110518%2FOEM04%2F110519901%2F1266 |archivedate=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=With Saturn's demise, Buick was selected to market a few rebadged Opel cars. For example, the current Insignia is marketed here as the Buick Regal, a key vehicle in the brand's turnaround. |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Regal utilizes [[Monocoque|unibody]] construction with [[galvanization|galvanized]] steel front fenders, hood, roof and door panels and [[Thermoplastic olefin|thermoplastic polyolefin]] (TPO) bumper covers.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p1\"/> The North American Regal weighs about {{Convert|13|lb|0|abbr=on}} more than an equivalent Opel Insignia due to increased structural support in the [[Pillar (car)|B-pillar]] necessary to meet U.S. [[Vehicle rollover|rollover]] standards.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/index.html|title=2011 Buick Regal|last=Lassa|first=Todd|date=November 2009|publisher=MotorTrend Magazine, Source Interlink Media|page=2|quote=The 2.4 comes with a GM Hydra-Matic 6T45 six-speed automatic, while the turbo comes with an Aisin AF40 six-speed automatic.|work=motortrend.com|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4VtdlaS?url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/engines.html|archivedate=2011-05-30|accessdate=2011-05-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing ===\nGM revealed the fifth generation Regal to North American dealers on October 14, 2009, and introduced the Regal to the public in November, 2009 at the [[LA Auto Show#2009|LA Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://archives.media.gm.com/archive/documents/domain_2/docId_57405_pr.html |title=Regal Named as Next Buick Sedan |date=2010-10-04 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4e8SLa1?url=http://archives.media.gm.com/archive/documents/domain_2/docId_57405_pr.html |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=...more than 1,000 dealers this week will be the first to learn the name of Buick\u2019s next mid-size sport sedan will be the Buick Regal. |url-status=dead }}</ref> Sales of the Regal began in February 2010. In North America, the Regal is positioned below the larger, more expensive [[Buick LaCrosse|LaCrosse]] and above the [[Buick Verano|Verano]] compact sedan which debuted late in calendar year 2011.\n\n=== Production ===\n[[File:Buick Regal CN II facelift China 2016-04-16.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal (China - facelift)]]\n\nProduction of the [[Shanghai GM]] variant of the Regal began in November 2008 and ended in July 2017. North American production at [[General Motors of Canada]]'s [[Oshawa, Ontario]], assembly plant was confirmed on November 25, 2009, and production began at [[Oshawa Car Assembly]] in February 2011.<ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25\"/><ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25-brand\"/> The initial production for the North American market was done together with its Opel twin the [[Opel Insignia]] in the [[Adam Opel AG]]'s [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Germany assembly plant from March 1, 2010 to March 25, 2011 (33,669 cars in 2010 and 12,637 in 2011).<ref name=\"Opel_FactFig2011\"/><ref name=\"Opel_Plant_display\">Production period according to a Foto on display at the Opel plant as seen on September 22, 2012, during the Open House on occasion of the 150-year Opel jubilee</ref>\n\n=== Trim levels ===\n\n==== {{anchor|CXL and CXL Turbo}} CXL ====\nThe Regal debuted in North America with a single engine, the 2.4L DOHC I4 engine and was rated at {{Convert|182|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|172|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. The 2.4L engine is mated to a GM [[Hydramatic|Hydra-Matic]] 6T45 six-speed\n\nThe 2011 Regal produced in North America was offered in one trim level, called CXL, and was offered with two engine choices and seven option packages. Buick had planned to offer a lower-level trim called CX with cloth seats and a higher level trim called CXS, but those trim levels have not yet been offered.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/future_plans.html |title=2011 Buick Regal |first=Todd |last=Lassa |date=November 2009 |work=motortrend.com |publisher=MotorTrend Magazine, Source Interlink Media |page=3 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4YVbINn?url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/future_plans.html |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=...Buick will add base, cloth-seat CX and high-zoot CXS trim levels. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== CXL Turbo ====\nThe CXL Turbo comes equipped with a [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] 2.0L direct-injected [[GM Ecotec engine|Ecotec]] DOHC I4 rated at {{Convert|220|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|258|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque, mated to either an [[Aisin Seiki Co.#Aisin AW|Aisin]] [[AWTF-80 SC|AF40]] 6-speed automatic or a 6-speed [[manual transmission]], making the Regal Turbo the first Buick model to be offered with a manual transmission since the [[Buick Skyhawk]] ended production in 1989. The 2.0L turbo is the first direct-injected turbocharged production car capable of running on any blend of gasoline or E85 ethanol.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/0221_regalturbo |title=Buick Regal Turbo Gets Industry-First Turbo Direct-Injected Engine with Flex-Fuel Capability |date=2011-02-21 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4gcFkpx?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/0221_regalturbo |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=The 2011 Buick Regal Turbo is the first direct-injected turbocharged production car capable of running on any blend of gasoline or E85 ethanol... |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== GS ====\n[[File:2011 Buick Verano (5490346021).jpg|thumb|left|2011 Buick Regal GS]]\nAt the [[North American International Auto Show#2010|2010 North American International Auto Show]] in Detroit, GM showed a concept GS version of the Regal based on the Opel Insignia [[Opel Performance Center|OPC]] and the Vauxhall Insignia VXR. The concept featured a 2.0L, {{convert|270|hp|0|abbr=on}}, {{convert|295|lbft|abbr=on}} high-output DOHC I4 turbocharged Ecotec engine, a 6-speed manual transmission and all-wheel drive.\n\nThe production GS leaves most of the concept specifications intact, but is front-wheel drive. The GS features Buick's Interactive Drive Control System with GS mode, a choice of an FGP Germany F40-6 six-speed manual or Aisin AF-40 (G2) six-speed automatic transmission, high performance brakes with [[Brembo]] front calipers and high performance strut (HiPerStrut) front suspension. 19&nbsp;inch wheels will be standard and 20&nbsp;inch forged aluminum wheels will be available. The GS is expected to accelerate from 0 to 60&nbsp;mph (97&nbsp;km/h) in under 7 seconds. The production version is equipped with GS-only high-output version of the Ecotec 2.0L turbo engine with {{Convert|270|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|295|lbft|abbr=on}} of torque. The GM LHU engine used in the GS trim makes 135&nbsp;hp per liter - Buick\u2019s highest specific output ever.<ref>{{cite web |last=Harman |first=Dan |title=Buick Regal |date=2014-02-05 |url=http://www.mojomotors.com/review/buick-regal/ |publisher=Mojo Motors |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NA6CL8No?url=http://www.mojomotors.com/review/buick-regal/ |archivedate=2014-02-05 |accessdate=2014-02-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The GS went on sale in fall 2011 as a 2012 model.<ref name=\"gm_pr_gs\">{{cite press release|title=Buick Regal GS Production Model Takes Sports Sedan Performance To A New Level For Buick|date=2010-11-04|publisher=General Motors Company|url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Nov/1104_gm_regal_gs|quote=Body style/driveline: four-door, five-passenger, front-engine transaxle. Front-wheel drive midsize sedan|accessdate=2011-05-30|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4bTpn44?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Nov/1104_gm_regal_gs|archivedate=2011-05-30|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"cad_2010-04\">{{cite web |url=http://www.caranddriver.com/features/10q1/2012_buick_regal_gs-feature |title=2012 Buick Regal GS - Feature |date=April 2010 |work=caranddriver.com |publisher=Hachette Filipacchi Media U.S., Inc |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4cOkeJx?url=http://www.caranddriver.com/features/10q1/2012_buick_regal_gs-feature |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=While Europeans will get an Insignia OPC with a {{Convert|325|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}, turbocharged V-6, the GS gets a higher-output version of the 2.0-liter turbo four found in the Regal. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Shanghai GM]] variant of Regal GS went on sale in China on September 15, 2011. This car has been localized. The output of the 2.0L Turbo SIDI engine is {{Convert|162|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}}, which is about {{Convert|40|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} less than the production US-model. The torque is {{convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}. and the top speed is claimed as {{convert|232|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}. The car is only offered in this case as a front-wheel-drive. There exist also some interior and exterior differences between the American and Chinese models.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buick.com.cn/RegalGS/ |title=2015\u6b3e\u65b0\u541b\u5a01GS \u7115\u65b0\u767b\u573a |publisher=Buick China |language=Chinese |date= |accessdate=2015-03-21}}</ref><ref name=shanghaigm_buick_gs>{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120131073541/http://buick.com.cn/RegalGS/specifications.aspx | url=http://www.buick.com.cn/RegalGS/specifications.aspx |title=\u522b\u514b\u5b98\u65b9\u7f51\u7ad9--\u541b\u5a01GS\u00b7\u667a\u9a71\u8c79-\u4ef7\u683c\u914d\u7f6e |publisher=Buick China | archivedate = 2012-01-31 | date= September 2011 | language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n==== Sport Touring Edition ====\nFor 2016, the Regal added a new Sport Touring Edition which included unique 18\" aluminum black pocket wheels and a rear lip spoiler.\n\n==== eAssist ====\n[[File:2012 Buick Regal eAssist WAS 2012 0830.JPG|thumb|2012 Buick Regal with optional [[BAS Hybrid#Generation II BAS (eAssist)|eAssist]] hybrid system]]\nBeginning in 2011, Buick began offering the [[BAS Hybrid#Generation II BAS (eAssist)|eAssist]] system in the Regal, The 2012 [[model year]] Regal is the second GM vehicle to offer eAssist after the 2012 [[Buick LaCrosse]]. The eAssist system is standard in the LaCrosse, but the eAssist powertrain is optional in the Regal.\n\nThe eAssist system adds a lithium-ion battery housed in the trunk, along with regenerative braking, engine stop/start, fuel cut-off, grille louvres that close at speed, underbody panels and low-rolling resistance tires. The eAssist system adds up to {{convert|15|hp|kW|abbr=on}} to the standard 2.4L Ecotec engine during acceleration. Fuel economy for the Regal with eAssist is estimated at {{convert|26|mpgus|abbr=on}} city, {{convert|37|mpgus|abbr=on}} highway.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/11chicago/buick/0208_Regal_eA |title=2012 Regal to Offer New eAssist\u2122 Fuel-Saving Technology |date=2011-02-08 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4n9b1i5?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/11chicago/buick/0208_Regal_eA |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=Mated to Regal\u2019s 2.4L Ecotec direct injection four-cylinder engine and next-generation six-speed automatic transmission... |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 Update ===\n[[File:2014 Regal.JPG|thumb|2014 Buick Regal eAssist]]\nGM revealed an updated 2014 Regal at the [[New York Auto Show#2013|2013 New York Auto Show]]. Changes include a revised interior and exterior, a boost in performance for the CXL Turbo up to 258&nbsp;hp (192&nbsp;kW) and 295&nbsp;lb\u00b7ft (400 N\u00b7m) of torque, and an available all-wheel drive option offered for the 2.0L engine/6-speed automatic transmission equipped vehicles. Changes for the GS include revised interior and exterior, a drop in power to match that of the CXL Turbo, and available an all-wheel drive option offered for the 2.0L / six-speed automatic transmission equipped vehicles. The six-speed manual transmission is still offered, but only in the front-wheel drive variant. Buick's [[Buick#VentiPorts|VentiPorts]] have reappeared starting with 2014 models, a styling feature unique to Buick that dates back to 1949.\n\nSeveral new safety features were added for the 2014 year, which include forward collision warning, lane-departure warning, blind-spot monitoring, rear cross-traffic alert, and a following-distance indicator. The foregoing are all part of a Driver Confidence package, while collision preparation, which pre-loads the brake system ahead of an imminent collision, and adaptive cruise control are available separately.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamm|first=John|title=2014 Buick Regal / Regal GS|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/news/2014-buick-regal-photos-and-info-news|work=Car and Driver|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"6\" |Shanghai GM Regal Engines (Petrol)\n|-\n!Engine model\n!Type\n!Displacement\n!Power\n!Torque\n!Year\n|-\n![[GM Family 1 engine#Generation III|'''1.6T''']]\n| rowspan=\"5\" |I4\n|1,598 cc\n|{{Convert|179|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} at 5,800 rpm\n|{{Convert|220|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,200\u20135,400 rpm\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2008\u20132017\n|-\n![[GM Family II engine|2.0]]\n|1,998 cc\n|{{Convert|147|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} at 6,200 rpm\n|{{Convert|190|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 4,600 rpm\n|-\n![[GM Ecotec engine#LDK|2.0T SIDI]]\n|1,998 cc\n|220 PS (162&nbsp;kW; 218&nbsp;hp) at 5,300 rpm\n|{{Convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,000\u20134,000 rpm\n|-\n![[GM Ecotec engine#LE5|2.4]]\n|2,384 cc\n|170 PS (125&nbsp;kW; 168&nbsp;hp) at 6,400 rpm\n|{{Convert|225|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} at 4,800 rpm\n|2008\u20132010\n|-\n![[GM Ecotec engine#LAF|2.4 SIDI]]\n|2,384 cc\n|{{Convert|186|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} at 6,200 rpm\n|{{Convert|240|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 4,800 rpm\n|2011\u20132017\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Sixth generation (2018) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sixth generation\n| image = 2018 Buick Regal Sportback Preferred II FWD, Ebony Twilight Metallic, front right.jpg\n| caption = 2018 Buick Regal Sportback\n| aka = {{unbulleted list|{{ill|\u522b\u514b\u541b\u5a01|zh|vertical-align=sup}} (Buick Regal; China)|[[Opel Insignia]] (Europe)|[[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] Insignia (United Kingdom)|[[Holden Commodore (ZB)]] (Australia)}}\n| production = 2017\u2013present<!--Until production has stopped, production dates should be \"present\" - DO NOT change to \"2020\"-->\n| model_years = 2018\u2013present<br>2018\u2013present ([[North America]])<!--Until production has stopped, production dates should be \"present\" - DO NOT change to \"2020\"-->\n| assembly = [[Germany]]: [[R\u00fcsselsheim am Main|R\u00fcsselsheim]] ([[Opel Automobile GmbH]])<br/>[[China]]: [[Shanghai]] ([[SAIC-GM]])\n| designer = Mark Adams<br />Malcolm Ward\n| body_style = 4-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] (China only)<br/>5-door [[fastback]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cargurus.com/Cars/2018-Buick-Regal-Sportback-Overview-c27060|title=Review of New Buick Regal}}</ref> (sportback)<br/>5-door [[Station wagon|wagon]]<ref name=\"wagon\">{{cite web|title=2018 Buick Regal Wagon Confirmed During Dealer Meeting|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2016/05/2018-buick-regal-wagon-confirmed-during-dealer-meeting/|last=Szymkowski|first=Sean|website=GM Authority|date=May 30, 2016|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n| platform = [[GM Epsilon platform#E2XX|E2XX platform]]\n| related = {{unbulleted list|[[Buick LaCrosse]]|[[Chevrolet Malibu]]}}\n| layout = [[FF layout]] / [[F4 layout]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list\n  |1.5 L ''[[GM small gasoline engine#LFV|LFV]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] ([[turbocharger|turbo]]) (China only)\n  |1.8 L [[Straight-4|I4]] (hybrid gasoline/electric) (30H China only)\n  |2.0 L ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] (turbo)\n  |3.6 L ''[[GM High Feature engine#LGX|LGX]]'' [[V6]]\n}}\n| transmission = [[AWF8F35|AWF8F45]] (8-speed) (I4 [[All-wheel drive|AWD]])<br>GM 9-speed Hydramatic 9T65 (I4 [[Front-wheel drive|FWD]], V6 [[All-wheel drive|AWD]])<br>[[Continuously Variable Transmission|CVT]] (30H China only)\n| wheelbase = {{convert|111.4|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|192.7|in|mm|abbr=on}}<br />{{convert|196.4|in|mm|abbr=on}} (TourX)\n| width = {{convert|73.3|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|57.3|in|mm|abbr=on}}<br />{{convert|58.4|in|mm|abbr=on}} (TourX)\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n}}[[File:Buick Regal 2.0T IMG 20180417 111121.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal sedan, rear view|alt=]]On April 4, 2017, an all-new sixth generation Buick Regal was introduced at GM's Design Dome in [[Warren, Michigan]] as a 2018 model in both [[Hatchback|liftback]] and [[station wagon]] versions. Buick Regal began sales in China on July 21, 2017.<ref>[http://media.gm.com/media/cn/en/buick/vehicles/All-New-Buick-Regal/2017.html \"All-New Buick Regal\"], ''Buick News China'', Retrieved on 16 August 2017.</ref> Similar to the previous generation, it is related to the [[Opel Insignia|Opel and Vauxhall Insignia]] sold in Europe and [[Holden Commodore (ZB)|Holden ZB Commodore]] in Australia, and like the previous generation, the vehicles were developed and are produced by Opel in Germany.\n\n===Regal Sportback===\nThe [[fastback]] version of the Regal, now branded as Regal Sportback, is the replacement for the Regal sedan. While the roofline is similar to that of its predecessor, the new liftback configuration provides added utility. It has grown larger in size, and is around {{Convert|300-500|lb|0|abbr=on}} lighter than the previous Regal.<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Buick Regal Will Be Lighter, Longer Than Current Model|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2015/07/2017-buick-regal-will-be-lighter-longer-than-current-model/|last=Singer|first=Drew|website=GM Authority|date=July 30, 2016|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref> It carries two versions of the ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' 2.0 L [[Turbocharged]] [[inline-4]] engine. [[Front-wheel drive]] models produce {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5400 rpm and {{convert|260|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2000 rpm, while the [[all-wheel drive]] model produces {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5500 and {{convert|295|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3000 rpm, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Buick Regal spy shots|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1102584_2018-buick-regal-spy-shots|last=Vijayenthiran|first=Viknesh|website=Motor Authority|date=February 27, 2016|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Regal TourX===\n[[File:Buick Regal TourX.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal TourX]]\n[[File:Buick Regal TourX rear.jpg|thumb|left|Rear view]]\nThe station wagon variant, named Regal TourX, was also introduced and went on sale at the same time as the hatchback, marking the first time since the demise of the [[Buick Roadmaster|Roadmaster]] in 1996 that Buick had a station wagon in its lineup. The TourX competes against the [[Volvo V60 Cross Country]], [[Audi A4 Allroad]], [[Subaru Outback]], and [[BMW 3 Series (F30)|BMW 3 Series wagon]], and offers up to 73.5 cubic feet of storage space behind the front seats, but only comes in all-wheel drive, along with a ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' turbocharged 2.0-liter four-cylinder producing an estimated {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|295|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} mated with an eight-speed automatic transmission.<ref name=\"wagon\" />\n\n===GS===\n[[File:Buick Regal II GS 001.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal GS sedan, front (China)]]\n[[File:Buick Regal II GS 002.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal GS sedan, rear (China)]]\nThe 2018 GS is the performance version of sixth generation Regal. This generation of GS sports a 3.6 liter [[GM High Feature engine|LGX]] V6 engine producing 310&nbsp;hp.\n\n===Discontinuation===\n\nIn December 2019, General Motors announced that it would end production of the Buick Regal for [[North America]] following the 2020 [[model year]], citing the popularity of the brand's [[sport utility vehicle]]s (SUV's), which have contributed to declining sales of Buick's passenger cars.  However, despite the discontinuation of the Regal in [[North America]], Buick will continue to produce the Regal for the [[China|Chinese]] market, where the vehicle recently received a mid-cycle facelift.<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2019/12/04/buick-regal-discontinued-gm-general-motors/2607182001/</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Sales ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Calendar year !! United States !! China !! Canada\n|-\n| 2009 || N/A || 80,401 || N/A\n|-\n| 2010 || 12,326 || 79,358 || 820\n|-\n| 2011 || 40,144 || 78,844 || 2,846\n|-\n| 2012 || 26,383 || 85,440 || 1,767\n|-\n| 2013 || 18,685 || 86,050 || 740\n|-\n| 2014 || 22,560 || 111,245 || 816\n|-\n| 2015 || 19,504 || 110,637 || 968\n|-\n| 2016 || 19,833 || 69,300 || 841\n|-\n| 2017 || 11,559 || 61,619 || 662\n|-\n| 2018 || 14,118 || 100,378 ||\n|-\n| 2019 || 10,363 || 123,587 ||\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Buick Gran Sport]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25\">{{cite press release \n |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |title=2011 Buick Regal to be built at the Oshawa Car Assembly Plant \n |date=2009-11-25 \n |publisher=General Motors Company \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4hXxaae?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |archivedate=2011-05-30 \n |accessdate=2011-05-30 \n |quote=North American production of the all-new 2011 Buick Regal was today confirmed for the Oshawa Car Assembly plant beginning in Q1 2011. \n |url-status=dead \n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25-brand\">{{cite press release \n |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |title=2011 Buick Regal to be built at the Oshawa Car Assembly Plant \n |publisher=GM Media Online \n |date=2009-11-25 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z26fCY4m?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |archivedate=2011-05-29 \n |accessdate=2011-05-28 \n |url-status=dead \n }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Opel_FactFig2011\">{{cite web \n|url= http://mediaassets.gmeuropearchive.info//ispace/pr/download/FactsFigures2011_www.pdf \n|title=Opel Facts and Figures 2011|page=34|author=Opel Corporate Communications\n|work=media.opel.com |date=February 2012\n|accessdate=20 September 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.gm.ca/gm/english/vehicles/buick/regal/overview Buick Regal official website - Canada]\n*[http://www.buick.com/regal-luxury-sport-sedan.html Buick Regal Official US Website]\n\n{{Buick Vehicles}}\n{{Buick postwar timeline}}\n{{Buick}}\n{{Buick China timeline}}\n\n[[Category:Buick vehicles|Regal]]\n[[Category:Flexible-fuel vehicles]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Mid-size cars]]\n[[Category:Sports sedans]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1973]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:2020s cars]]\n[[Category:Personal luxury cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mid-sized car model}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Buick Regal\n| image = Buick Regal 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = 2018 Buick Regal\n| manufacturer = [[Buick]] ([[General Motors]])\n| aka = [[Opel Insignia]] (Europe)<br />[[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] Insignia (United Kingdom)<br />[[Holden Commodore (ZB)]] (Australia, New Zealand)\n| model_years = '''North America'''<br />1973\u20132004<br />2011\u2013present<!--Until production has stopped, production dates should be \"present\" - DO NOT change to \"2020\"--><br />'''China'''<br />1999\u2013present\n| class = [[Mid-size|Mid-size car]] ([[D-segment|D]]) (1973-1987, 2009-present)<br />[[Mid-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[E-segment|E]]) (1988-2004)\n| layout = [[FR layout]] (1973\u20131987)<br />[[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|FF layout]] (1988\u2013present)<br />[[F4 layout]] (2008\u20132020)\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = [[Buick Skylark#1968\u20131972|Buick Skylark]] (1972)\n| successor = [[Buick LaCrosse]] (for Regal, 1988\u20132004)\n}}\nThe '''Buick Regal''' is an upscale [[mid-size]]d [[car|automobile]] that was first introduced by [[Buick]] for the 1973 model year. The model was originally positioned as a [[personal luxury car]], and typically offered in both [[Coup\u00e9|coupe]] and [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] forms until 1997, when the Regal became sedan-only due to the decline of the personal luxury coupe market. For certain model years between 1973 and 2004, the Regal shared bodies and powertrains with the similar [[Buick Century]], although the Regal was positioned as a more upmarket vehicle.\n\nThe Regal was discontinued in the North American market in 2004, being succeeded by the [[Buick LaCrosse]]. In 2008, a new version of the Regal was introduced for the Chinese market, which is a [[Rebadging|badge engineered]] version of the [[Opel Insignia]]. The new Regal was introduced to the North American market in 2011, positioned as a mid-size vehicle. A new model was introduced for 2018, which is offered in a [[liftback]] sedan and a \"TourX\" [[station wagon]] version.  GM plans to discontinue the Regal in the North American market after the 2020 model year, making Buick exclusively an SUV/CUV marque there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2019/12/04/buick-regal-discontinued-gm-general-motors/2607182001/|title=General Motors kills the Buick Regal: GM continues to cut passenger cars|last=Bomey|first=Nathan|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/386005/buick-regal-dead-after-2020my/|title=Buick Regal Dead After 2020MY Because Customers Want Crossovers|work=[[Motorsport Network|Motor1.com]]|last=Padeanu|first=Adrian|date=4 December 2019|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30120611/buick-regal-dead/|title=Buick Regal Is Dead, Leaving Buick with an All-SUV Lineup|work=[[Car and Driver]]|last=Capparella|first=Joey|date=4 December 2019|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== First generation (1973) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = First generation\n| image          = File:1974 Buick Regal (26756596603).jpg\n| caption        = 1974 Buick Regal coupe\n| aka              = Buick Century Regal\n| model_years    = 1973\u20131977\n| assembly       = {{unbulleted list|United States: [[Flint, Michigan]] ([[Buick City]])|[[Framingham, Massachusetts]] ([[Framingham Assembly]])|[[Fremont, California]] ([[Fremont Assembly]])|[[Lakewood Heights, Atlanta|Lakewood Heights, Georgia]] ([[Lakewood Assembly]])}}\n| engine         = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Buick V6 engine#231|Buick]]'' [[V6 engine|V6]] (gasoline)|{{convert|350|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Buick V8 engine#350|Buick]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]] (gasoline)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|455|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Buick V8 engine#455|Buick]]'' [[V8 engine|V8]] (gasoline)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| transmission   = {{unbulleted list|3-speed ''[[Turbo-Hydramatic]] [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM350|350]]'' automatic<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|3-speed ''[[Turbo-Hydramatic]] [[Turbo-Hydramatic#Super Turbine 400 .2F THM400 .2F THM375 .2F 3L80 .2F 3L80HD|400]]'' automatic<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| wheelbase      = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|112|in|mm|abbr=on}} (coupe)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|116|in|mm|abbr=on}} (sedan)<ref name=\"carbrochure\">{{cite web|author=Dusan Ristic-Petrovic |url=http://oldcarbrochures.com/new/021110/1974%20Buick%20Century/1974%20Buick%20Century-06.html |title=File: 1974 Buick Century/1974 Buick Century-06 |publisher=Oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-08}}</ref>}}\n| length         = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|212|in|mm|abbr=on}} (coupe)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|216|in|mm|abbr=on}} (sedan)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| height        = {{unbulleted list|{{convert|53.3|in|mm|abbr=on}} (coupe)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>|{{convert|54.1|in|mm|abbr=on}} (sedan)<ref name=\"carbrochure\"/>}}\n| body_style     = 2-door [[coupe]]<br />4-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| related        = {{unbulleted list|[[Buick Century#1973.E2.80.931977|Buick Century]]|[[Chevrolet El Camino#Fourth generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Chevrolet El Camino]]|[[Chevrolet Chevelle#Third generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Chevrolet Malibu]]|[[Chevrolet Monte Carlo#Second generation|Chevrolet Monte Carlo]]|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass#Fourth Generation - 1973.E2.80.931977|Oldsmobile Cutlass]]|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme#Third generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]]|[[Pontiac Grand Am#1973.E2.80.931975|Pontiac Grand Am]]|[[Pontiac Grand Prix#Third generation .281973.E2.80.931977.29|Pontiac Grand Prix]]}}\n| platform       = [[GM A platform (RWD)|A-body]]\n| layout         = [[FR layout]]\n| sp             = us\n}}\n\n[[File:Nona6.jpg|thumb|left|1973 Buick Regal coupe]]\n[[File:Buick-Regal-(A-body)-Vilnius-Lithuania-front.jpg|thumb|left|1976 Buick Regal sedan]]\n[[File:Buick-Regal-(A-body)-Vilnius-Lithuania-back.jpg|thumb|left|1976 Buick Regal sedan]]\n\n[[Buick]] had been the first GM division to bring a [[personal luxury car]] to market with its 1963 [[Buick Riviera|Riviera]], but was otherwise slow to react to the developing lower-priced mid-size personal luxury market, which [[Pontiac]] created with the 1969 [[Pontiac Grand Prix|Grand Prix]] and [[Chevrolet]] with the [[Chevrolet Monte Carlo|Monte Carlo]] the following year, 1970. At the same time, [[Oldsmobile]] added a formal notchback coup\u00e9 to its intermediate line, the [[Cutlass Supreme]], in 1970 and that model soon became Olds' best selling intermediate. Buick did not get its own personal luxury coupe until the GM intermediates were redesigned in 1973, the so-called \"Colonnade\" cars that eliminated hardtop models completely. In a curious name swap, the Skylark name was dropped from Buick's intermediate line and instead the Century nameplate, last used in the 1950s, was revived for them.\n\nA highly trimmed, two-door [[coupe]], the first Regal, officially marketed as the \"Century Regal Colonnade Hardtop coupe\", shared its front and rear styling with its Century parent with distinctions amounting to differing grilles and taillight lenses. The Regal shared the same \"Colonnade\" [[Hardtop|pillared hardtop]] roofline (a [[hardtop]] with [[Pillar (car)|B-pillars (center pillars)]] but frameless doors unlike a sedan body) and greenhouse (window area) with the Grand Prix, Monte Carlo, and Cutlass Supreme as well as the lower-priced Buick Century Luxus coupe. Like its corporate cousins, the Regal (and Luxus) featured the newly fashionable opera windows, which were small fixed rear-side windows surrounded by sheetmetal, instead of the traditional roll-down windows.\n\nFor the first [[model year]] in 1973, the Regal nameplate was only used for Buick's version of the GM intermediate [[personal luxury car|personal luxury]] [[coupe]], but the following year gained a [[sedan (car)|sedan]] companion (there was no Regal [[station wagon]]).\n\nRegal interiors were generally more luxurious than lesser Century models with woodgrain trim on [[dashboard]] and [[door panel]]s, along with door-pull straps and [[bench seat]]s with center [[armrest]]s with cloth, velour, or vinyl upholstery. Optionally available throughout the run was a 60/40 split bench seat with [[armrest]]. For 1976 and 1977, the Regal [[coup\u00e9|coupe]] was available with the S/R option that included reclining bucket seats with corduroy upholstery.\n\nThe model lasted five years with minimal changes, although there was a fairly substantial facelift in coupes for 1976 (sedans retained their original 1973 sheetmetal through 1977), which incorporated the recently-legalized rectangular headlights (horizontally mounted on coupes, and vertically on [[sedan (car)|sedan]]s\u2014much like the mid-1960s Pontiacs). The Regal coupe sold reasonably well, although it lagged behind the Monte Carlo and Cutlass Supreme which had become the best-selling cars in America by 1976.\n\nThe Regal was most commonly powered by [[Buick V8 engine#350|Buick's {{convert|350|cuin|L|abbr=on}} V8]], which was standard equipment on all models for 1973 and 1974, and optional on coupes but standard on sedans from 1975 to 1977, and the larger [[Buick V8 engine#455|{{convert|455|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} V8]] was optional for 1973 and 1974 models only. Starting in 1975, Regal coupes came standard with Buick's resurrected {{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[V6 engine]] previously offered on the 1964\u20131967 [[Buick Skylark|Skylark]]; the engine's tooling had been sold to [[Kaiser Motors]] for use in [[Jeep]] models (Kaiser was purchased by American Motors in 1970 and Jeep became an AMC division) and sold back to GM by AMC in 1974. For 1975 and 1976, the Century and Regal were the only mid-sized cars in America to offer V6 engines. The bolt pattern for this vehicle is 5\u00d7{{convert|4+3/4|in|mm|1}}.\n\nThe Century designation was quietly dropped from the Regal for 1975.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Second generation (1978) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Second generation\n| image = '87 Buick Regal Grand National (Auto classique A&W Ch\u00e2teauguay '12).JPG\n| caption = 1987 Buick Regal Grand National\n| model_years = 1978\u20131987\n| layout = [[FR layout]]\n| assembly = United States: {{ubl\n|[[Flint, Michigan]]\n|[[Lakewood Heights, Atlanta|Lakewood Heights, Georgia]]\n|[[Arlington, Texas]]\n|[[Framingham, Massachusetts]]\n|[[Fremont, California]]\n|[[Pontiac, Michigan]]\n|[[Kansas City, Missouri]] (Leeds)\n}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|108|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| related = {{ubl\n|[[Buick Century]]\n|[[Chevrolet El Camino]]\n|[[Chevrolet Malibu]]\n|[[Chevrolet Monte Carlo]]\n|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass]]\n|[[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]]\n|[[Pontiac Bonneville]]\n|[[Pontiac Grand Am]]\n|[[Pontiac Grand Prix]]\n|[[Pontiac Le Mans]]\n}}\n| engine = {{ubl\n|{{convert|196|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#3.2|Buick V6]]\n|{{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#LD5|Buick V6]]\n|{{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#LD5|Buick V6]] [[Turbocharger|Turbocharged]]\n|{{convert|252|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Buick V6 engine#4.1|Buick V6]]\n|{{convert|260|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Oldsmobile Diesel engine|Oldsmobile Diesel]] [[V6 engine|V6]]\n|{{convert|265|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Pontiac V8 engine#265|Pontiac V8]]\n|{{convert|301|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Pontiac V8 engine#301|Pontiac V8]]\n|{{convert|305|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Chevrolet Small-Block engine#305|Chevrolet]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n|{{convert|307|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Oldsmobile V8 engine#307|Oldsmobile V8]]\n|{{convert|350|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Oldsmobile Diesel engine|Oldsmobile Diesel]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n| transmission = {{ubl\n|3-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]\n|3-speed [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM200|THM200]] [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n|4-speed [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM200-4R|THM200-4R]] automatic\n}}\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]<br />4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br />5-door [[station wagon]]\n| platform = [[GM A platform (RWD)|A-body]] (1978\u20131981)<br />[[GM G platform (RWD)|G-body]] (1981\u20131987)\n| sp = us\n}}\n\nA downsized Regal appeared for the 1978 model year with Buick's new {{convert|196|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[V6 engine]] as standard equipment and a revised version of the venerable {{convert|231|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} V6 as an option (which became standard for 1980). Initially, a three-speed [[manual transmission]] was standard but this was later replaced by an automatic. At the time of introduction, Regals were available exclusively as [[coup\u00e9]]s with the [[Buick Century|Century]] nameplate applied to bread-and-butter sedans and [[station wagon]]s.<ref name=\"buick\">{{Cite book | ref = SCBuick | title = Standard Catalog of Buick, 1903-2004 | edition = 3 | first = John | last = Gunnell | publisher = Krause Publications, Inc. | location = Iola, WI | page = 182 | date = 2004 | isbn = 0-87349-760-0 }}</ref> In January 1982 the Century was replaced by an all-new car on the [[front-wheel drive]] [[GM A platform (1982)|A platform]], which meant that the Regal gained a four-door sedan and five-door station wagon - essentially facelifted and [[Badge|rebadged]] versions of the previous year's [[rear-wheel drive]] Century. It was the first time the name appeared on a full model lineup. The wagon was discontinued after 1983, and the sedan dropped from the lineup the next year.<ref name=stdB>[[#SCBuick|Gunnell]], pp. 218, 224</ref> This generation Regal lasted ten years. The base model was equipped with softer-riding luxury [[Suspension (vehicle)|suspension]], and did not offer a manual transmission in later years.\n\n[[File:Buick Regal -- 08-14-2009.jpg|thumb|left|1978\u20131979 Buick Regal]]\n[[File:Regal A-Body.JPG|thumb|left|1980 Buick Regal]]\n[[File:1982 Buick Regal Wagon two-tone green, front right.jpg|thumb|left|1982 Buick Regal Estate Wagon]]\n[[File:Buick Regal G-Body.jpg|thumb|left|1982\u20131987 Buick Regal]]\n\nThe 1978 Regal could be equipped with a {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} [[Turbocharged]] V6 engine with [[automatic transmission]], and was known as a Regal Sport Coupe. Turbo versions were offered with either a two- or a four-barrel [[carburetor]]. The [[Buick LeSabre]] was also available with the turbocharged engine. The only other turbocharged cars available in the U.S. market in 1978 were imports from [[Mercedes-Benz]], [[Porsche 930|Porsche]] and [[Saab Automobile|Saab]]. The Regal Sport Coupe also included a firm [[Car handling|handling]] suspension with larger tires and sport wheels.  Bucket seats and a center console with a T-shifter were also available.\n\nA major facelift for 1981 gave the Regal a much more aerodynamic profile, helping make it possible for the car to compete on the [[NASCAR]] racing circuit. The sloping [[Hood (car)|hood]] and nose of the car made it the favorite of several NASCAR teams. [[Richard Petty]] drove one to victory in the [[1981 Daytona 500]], and the car won a majority of the 1981 and 1982 seasons races and won the NASCAR manufacturers title in 1981 and 1982.\n\n[[V8 engine|V8]]s for street use were still available, but had shrunk to {{convert|265|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} (1980 and 1981 only, [[Pontiac]] built), and the V6 was rapidly gaining popularity. From 1986 to 1987, the [[Oldsmobile V8 engine#307|{{convert|307|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8]] was available as an option. The {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} 2-bbl V6 was standard. The [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM200-4R|200-4R]] [[Overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]] [[Transmission (mechanics)|transmission]] was an option with either engine.\n\nFor 1980, the Regal was offered in a special '''Somerset Limited Edition''' [[Trim level (automobile)|trim]] which featured unique tan and dark blue designer exterior paint, wire wheel covers, sport [[Wing mirror|mirrors]], and chrome Somerset badging. The interior had tan and blue plush [[velour]] [[Upholstery#Automobile upholstery|upholstery]], brushed [[Chrome plating#Automotive use|chrome]] trim, and additional Somerset badging. A Somerset Limited Edition model was also offered on the restyled 1981 Regal. It had unique dark sandstone and camel exterior paint, sport mirrors, and turbine wheels. The interior plush velour upholstery was camel with dark brown piping.\n\n=== Grand National, Turbo-T, T-Type, and GNX ===\nIn February 1982, the Regal Grand National debuted, which was named for the [[NASCAR Sprint Cup Series|NASCAR Winston Cup Grand National Series]] (the \"Grand National\" term was part of the Cup series nomenclature until 1986).<ref>http://legendarydreamcargarage.com/dreamcargarage/539</ref> Buick had won the Manufacturers Cup in 1981 and 1982, and wanted to capitalize on its success: \"What wins on Sunday, sells on Monday\". These 1982 cars were not painted black, which may confuse those not familiar with them. All started out as charcoal gray Regals that were shipped off to a subcontractor for finishing.\n\nOriginally intended for a run of 100 units, Cars and Concepts of [[Brighton, Michigan]], retrofitted 215 Regals with the GN package. Most obvious was the light silver gray firemist paint added to each side. Red [[Pinstriping#Automobiles|pinstripes]] and billboard shadow lettering proclaiming \"Buick\" were applied. The wheel opening moldings and [[rocker panel]] moldings were blacked out using black vinyl tape. Finally, a front air dam and [[rear spoiler]] were installed. On the inside, special \"Lear-Siegler\" seats were installed. These seats are fully adjustable and were covered with silver brandon cloth with black vinyl inserts. The front seat had Buick's \"6\" emblem embroidered onto them. Also, a special clock delete plate was added to the [[Dashboard|instrument panel]] which contained the yellow and orange \"6\" logo and the words \"Grand National Buick Motor Division\".)\n\nThe 1982 GN came with a [[naturally aspirated]] {{convert|252|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V6 engine with {{convert|125|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|205|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]] at 2000&nbsp;rpm. Of the 215 Regal Grand Nationals produced in 1982, at least 35 were based on the Buick Regal Sport coupe package with the turbocharged {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} V6 engine with {{convert|175|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|275|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2600&nbsp;rpm. There were only 2022 Sport coupes produced in 1982, and the number of cars with both the GN and Sport coupe packages is estimated to be fewer than 50.\n\nFor 1983, there was no Grand National. The Sport coupe model was renamed the [[T-Type]]; 3,732 were produced ({{convert|190|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 1600&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2400&nbsp;rpm). The T-Type had been used on other Buicks, starting with the [[Buick Riviera|Riviera]] in 1981 (in 1979 and 1980, it was the S Type). The 1983 Regal T-Type featured tube [[Exhaust manifold|headers]], Hydro-Boost II [[brake]]s, 200-4R 4-speed overdrive trans and 3.42 [[rear axle]] (7.5\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autotraderclassics.com/car-article/Future+Collectible%3A+1986+Buick+Grand+National*T_Type-66683.xhtml |title=Buick Grand National Buyer's Guide |publisher=Autotraderclassics.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-10}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Buick T-Type (2669441886).jpg|thumb|Buick Regal T-Type]]\n\nFor 1984, the Grand National returned, now in all black paint. The [[turbocharged]] {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} became standard and was refined with [[sequential fuel injection]], [[distributor]]-less computer controlled [[Ignition system|ignition]], and boasted {{convert|200|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4400&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|300|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2400&nbsp;rpm. Only 5,204 turbo Regals were produced that year, only 2,000 of which were Grand Nationals. Because this was the first year production of the computer controlled sequential fuel injection and distributor-less ignition, this is often considered the year and model that started the development of the legendary [[intercooled]] Grand Nationals. The performance of this package was well ahead of its time and the \"little V6\" easily kept up with the bigger V8s. [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] performance was listed at 15.9 seconds at stock boost levels of {{convert|10|psi|bar|abbr=on}}, while for the same year, the [[Chevrolet Camaro (third generation)|Chevrolet Camaro]] V6 was listed at 17.0 and the [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|Chevrolet Corvette]] at 15.2 seconds.<ref name=cd_corvette>\n{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/1984-chevrolet-corvette-c4-archived-road-test\n|title=1984 Corvette (C4) \n|date=1983-03-01\n|publisher=Car and Driver\n}}</ref> Soon, performance enthusiasts determined the modifications that worked and the Grand Nationals easily broke into the 13-second territory. All Grand Nationals had the [[Lear Siegler]]-made cloth/leather interior which was only available for this year. An estimated 200 of the 1984 Grand Nationals were produced with the T-Top option which makes these the rarest of the Grand Nationals.\n\nFor 1986, a modified engine design with air-air intercooling boosted the performance even further to a specified {{convert|235|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|330|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 2400&nbsp;rpm. The Grand Nationals (quantity 5,512) and T-Types (quantity 2,384) were both produced in 1986. For 1987, performance reached {{convert|245|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|355|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. Buick dropped the T-Type package for Regal for 1987 models and opted for a \"T\" sport package instead. There were only 7,896 turbo Regals produced in 1986. In 1987, when turbo Regals reached their peak in popularity, a total of 27,590 turbo Regals were produced through December, with those models produced between September and December of that year window stickered as \"1987\u00bd Buick Grand National\" vehicles.\n\n[[File:WO2T.jpg|thumb|1987 Regal turbo-T Limited with rare blackout trim package]]\n\nFor 1987, a lightweight WE4 (turbo T) option was offered. Only 1,547 of this variant were produced. The differences between a WE4 and the Grand National were the interior trim package, wheels, exterior badging, aluminum bumper supports, and aluminum rear [[drum brake]]s as opposed to the Grand National's cast iron, making the WE4 a lighter and faster car. The rear spoiler was only available as a dealer installed option. Nineteen eighty-seven was the only year that the LC2 turbo option was available on any Regal, making it possible to even see a Limited with a vinyl [[Landau (automobile)|landau roof]] and a [[power bulge]] turbo hood. Turbo Regal Limiteds were one of the rarest models of turbo Regals produced second only to the GNX at 1,035 turbo Limiteds. Turbo Regal Limiteds could be ordered with many options with most having chrome external trim but for $35 could have been built with the full black-out trim option making them extremely rare. Limiteds were treated to a very luxurious interior with plush carpeting and optional bench pillow seats and a [[Gear stick|column shift]]. The 1987 model would be the end of the manufacture of the [[Rear wheel drive|RWD]] \"G-Body\" Regal, but [[General Motors|GM]] had to extend the build of the Grand National to meet customer demand into December.\n[[File:Buick GNX (20206519195).jpg|thumb|Buick Regal GNX]]\n[[File:Buick GNX (20180268696).jpg|thumb|Buick Regal GNX]]\nFor the final year, 1987, Buick introduced the limited production GNX, for \"Grand National Experimental\", at $29,900. Made in partnership with [[Linamar|McLaren Performance Technologies]]/[[American Specialty Cars|ASC]], Buick produced only 547 GNs with the interior trim package, that were then sent off to [[Linamar|McLaren]] and upgraded into the Buick GNX. Buick underrated the GNX at {{Convert|276|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 4400&nbsp;rpm and a very substantial {{convert|360|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3000&nbsp;rpm of [[Torque#Machine torque|torque]],<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=100661\n|title=1987 Buick Regal GNX\n|website=Carfolio.com\n|accessdate=2018-09-23\n|date=2013-02-28}}</ref> although actual output is {{convert|300|bhp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|420|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"GNXPerf\">{{cite web|url=http://home.att.net/~buickGNX/GNX/perf.htm |title=GNX Performance |work=BuickGNX.com |accessdate=2007-07-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630104145/http://home.att.net/~buickGNX/GNX/perf.htm |archivedate=June 30, 2007 }}</ref> This was created to be the \"Grand National to end all Grand Nationals.\" Changes made included a special [[Garrett AiResearch]] T-3 [[turbocharger]] with a ceramic-impeller blowing through a more efficient and significantly larger capacity [[intercooler]] with a \"Cermatel (ceramic-aluminum) coated\" pipe connecting the intercooler to the engine. A GNX specific E-EPROM, low-restriction exhaust with dual [[muffler]]s, reprogrammed turbo Hydramatic 200-4R transmission with a custom [[torque converter]] and transmission cooler, and unique [[Differential (mechanical device)|differential]] cover/[[Panhard]] bar included more of the performance modifications. Exterior styling changes include vents located on each front fender, 16&nbsp;inch black mesh style wheels with VR-speed rated tires, and deletion of the hood and fender emblems. The interior changes of the GNX included a serial number on the dash plaque and a revised instrument cluster providing [[Stewart-Warner]] [[Analog device|analog gauges]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Popular Mechanics |date=March 1987 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HOMDAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> including an analog turbo [[boost gauge]]. Performance was measured faster than the [[Ferrari F40]] and the [[Porsche 930]] with a [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] time of 12.7 seconds at {{Convert|113.1|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} (0.3 and 0.8 seconds quicker, 2.9 and {{convert|13.3|mph|0|abbr=on}} faster) and a 0-{{convert|60|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} time of 4.6 seconds (0.4 and 0.3 seconds quicker, respectively).<ref>[http://imgur.com/gallery/uzXOy], ''MotorTrend'', accessed Aug 11, 2016.</ref>\nGNX #001 is the 1986 prototype currently owned by Buick and sometimes makes appearances at car shows around the US. The GNX used a unique [[torque arm]] that was mounted to a special, GNX only, rear differential cover, for increased [[Traction (engineering)|traction]]. The torque arm rear suspension alters the suspension geometry, making the body lift while planting the rear tires down, resulting in increased traction.\n\nThe stealthy appearance of the all-black GNX and Grand National (and the resemblance of its grill to his helmet's mouthpiece), coupled with the fact that the Grand National was initially released during the popularity of ''[[Star Wars]]'' movies, earned it the title \"[[Darth Vader]]'s Car\". [[Car and Driver]] covered the GNX model's introduction with the headline \"Lord Vader, your car is ready.\"  Due to the turbocharged six cylinder engine, the Buick make, and the black paint Grand Nationals were sometimes referred to as the \"Dark Side\". The \"Dark Side\" contrasted with the more common V8 [[Ford Mustang (third generation)|Mustangs]] and Camaros that were popular at the time.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Third generation (1988) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Third generation\n| image = Buick gray.jpg\n| caption = 1988\u20131989 Buick Regal Limited coupe\n| model_years = 1988&ndash;1996\n| production = 1987\u2013October 1996<ref>https://www.cars.com/reviews/chicagotribunecoms-view-1420689074485/</ref>\n| transmission = 4-speed automatic<br />1988\u201392: [[GM 4T60 transmission|4T60]]<br />1993\u201396: [[GM 4T60-E transmission|4T60-E]]\n| engine = 2.8 L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Transverse|X]]'' [[V6]]<br />3.1 L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation II|X]]'' [[V6]]<br />3.8 L ''[[Buick V6 engine#3800 V6|Buick]]'' [[V6]]\n| assembly = [[Oshawa, Ontario]], Canada ([[GM Canada]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coupe]]<br />4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|107.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = 1988\u201389 2dr: {{convert|192.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1990\u201391 2dr: {{convert|191.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1992\u201394 2dr: {{convert|193.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1995\u201396 2dr: {{convert|193.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1990\u201391 4dr: {{convert|194.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1992\u201394 Custom & GS 4dr: {{convert|194.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1992\u201394 Limited 4dr: {{convert|196|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1995 4dr: {{convert|193.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />1996 4dr: {{convert|194.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|72.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = Sedan: {{convert|54.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<br />Coupe: {{convert|53|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| related = [[Chevrolet Lumina#First generation .281990.E2.80.931994.29|Chevrolet Lumina]]<br />[[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme#Fifth generation .281988.E2.80.931997.29|Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]]<br />[[Pontiac Grand Prix#Fifth generation .281988.E2.80.931996.29|Pontiac Grand Prix]]\n| platform = [[GM W platform|W-body]]\n| layout = [[FF layout]]\n| designer = \n| sp = us\n}}\n\n[[File:'88-'89 Buick Regal (Orange Julep).JPG|thumb|left|1988\u20131989 Buick Regal GS coupe]]\n[[File:Buick Regal 2 -- 10-30-2009.jpg|thumb|left|1990\u20131994 Buick Regal GS sedan]]\n[[File:1991 Buick Regal Limited.jpg|thumb|left|1991 Buick Regal Limited coupe]]\n[[File:Buick Regal coupe.jpg|thumb|left|1995\u20131996 Buick Regal coupe]]\n[[File:95-96 Buick Regal.jpg|thumb|left|1996 Buick Regal sedan]]\n\nA new Regal appeared in October 1987 on the [[GM W platform]] as the first vehicle on that platform;<ref>http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1987-08-30-8703050938-story.html</ref> this generation ran with few changes for nine years. Though the new Regal returned to Buick's original concept in being offered only as a coupe and in being aimed once again squarely at the personal luxury buyer, it departed from tradition in being the first front-wheel drive model, and in having no serious performance option or edition. Neither a [[V8 engine|V8]] engine nor a turbocharged [[V6]] was offered; the only engine available for 1988 was the Chevrolet 2.8&nbsp;L V6, producing {{convert|125|hp|abbr=on}}.\n\nFrom 1990, owing to the declining personal luxury car market, the Regal was again offered as a four-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] (as were the Cutlass Supreme and Grand Prix the same year, the latter offered as a sedan for the first time).\n\nThe Regal was initially offered in base ''Custom'' and upscale ''Limited'' trim lines. For 1989, the ''[[Buick Gran Sport#Regal GS / Regal Gran Sport|Gran Sport]]'' trim line was added, featuring aluminum wheels, body side cladding and a console mounted shifter attached to the 4-speed automatic. For 1990, the Regal gained the option of the Buick 3.8&nbsp;L V6. The 3800 V6 was unique to the Regal, differentiating it from the mechanically similar [[Chevrolet Lumina]], [[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]] and [[Pontiac Grand Prix]]. Anti-lock brakes were made standard on all but the base ''Custom'' cars from 1992, and the grille was redesigned again for 1993. Along with the new look came an electronically controlled [[automatic transmission]] and [[Buick LeSabre|LeSabre]]-like rear lights and bumper. For 1993, a driver's side [[airbag]] was added, along with standard [[Anti-lock braking system|ABS]] on all models, standard power windows, and {{convert|20|hp|0|abbr=on}} more in the base engine due to a revised intake manifold and cylinder head. The ''Limited'' coupe was deleted; only the ''Custom'' and ''Gran Sport (GS)'' coupes remained. Dual airbags were new for 1995 along with a new interior.\n\nFor 1996, the larger {{convert|3791|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} V6 engine became the ''3800 Series II'' and gained {{convert|35|hp|0|abbr=on}}. {{citation needed span|Although 1996 was the last model year of this model, sales continued into 1997 as the replacement model was late (arriving in January 1997).|date=October 2018}}\n\n=== Engines ===\n* 1988\u20131989 2.8&nbsp;L (170&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation II|Chevrolet LB6]] [[MPFI|MFI]] [[V6]], {{Convert|125|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|160|lbft|0|abbr=on}}\n* 1989\u20131993 3.1&nbsp;L (191&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation II|Chevrolet LH0]] MFI V6, {{Convert|140|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|180|lbft|0|abbr=on}}\n* 1994\u20131996 3.1&nbsp;L (191&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#Generation III|Chevrolet L82]] SFI V6, {{Convert|160|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|185|lbft|Nm|abbr=on}}\n* 1990\u20131995 3.8&nbsp;L (231&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[L27 Naturally Aspirated|Buick L27]] V6, {{Convert|170|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|220|lbft|0|abbr=on}}\n* 1996 3.8&nbsp;L (231&nbsp;in\u00b3) [[Buick V6 engine#L36 Naturally Aspirated|Buick L36]] V6, {{Convert|200|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|225|lbft|Nm|abbr=on}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n== {{anchor|Fourth}} Fourth generation (1997) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Fourth generation\n| image = Buick Regal GSE.jpg\n| caption = Buick Regal (US)\n| aka = Chevrolet Lumina (Philippines)\n| production = {{ubl | 1996\u20132004 | China: 1999&ndash;2008 || Philippines: 2005&ndash;2006 }}\n| model_years = North America: 1997&ndash;2004\n| assembly = {{unbulleted list|Canada: [[Oshawa, Ontario]], [[GM Canada]]|China: [[Shanghai]], [[Shanghai GM]]}}\n| predecessor = \n| successor = [[Buick LaCrosse]]\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| layout = [[FF layout]]\n| platform = [[GM W platform|W-body 2nd Gen]]\n| engine = 2.0 L ''[[Family II engine#L34|L34]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (China)<br />2.5&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#China|LB8]]'' [[V6 engine|V6]] (China)<br />3.0&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LW9|LW9]]'' [[V6 engine|V6]] (China)<br />3.8 L [[Buick V6 engine#Series II|3800 Series II]] [[V6]]\n| transmission = 5-speed manual (China, 2.0 L only) <br /> 4-speed [[GM 4T60-E transmission#4T60-E|4T60-E]] automatic <br /> 4-speed [[GM 4T60-E transmission#4T65-E|4T65-E]] automatic <br /> 4-speed [[GM 4T60-E transmission#4T65-E|4T65-E HD]] automatic\n| wheelbase = {{convert|109.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|196.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|72.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|56.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = \n| related = {{unbulleted list |[[Buick Century#1997.E2.80.932005|Buick Century]]|[[Chevrolet Impala#Eighth|Chevrolet Impala]]|[[Chevrolet Monte Carlo#Sixth|Chevrolet Monte Carlo]]|[[Oldsmobile Intrigue]]|[[Pontiac Grand Prix#Sixth generation .281997.E2.80.932003.29|Pontiac Grand Prix]]}}\n| designer = Wayne Cherry<br />Wayne Kady (1993)\n| sp = us\n}}\n{{see also|Buick Century#1997\u20132005|l1=Buick Century \u00a7 1997\u20132005}}\n\n[[File:Buick Regal.jpg|thumb|left|1997\u20132004 Buick Regal sedan]]\n\nFor the 1997 model year, the Century and Regal once again rode upon the same platform; the revised [[GM W platform|W platform]] that was shared with the [[Oldsmobile Intrigue]], the [[Pontiac Grand Prix]], the [[Chevrolet Lumina]] and [[Chevrolet Monte Carlo]].<ref>https://adage.com/article/news/buick-s-regal-read-costly-web-launch/263/</ref> The Regal coupe was discontinued.\n\nDifferences between the Regal and Century were mostly cosmetic. As the upmarket version, the Regal offered larger engines and fancier trim, and once again boasted a newer version of the 3.8&nbsp;L V6. While the Century was mainly a reliable, economy-minded car based upon the W-body, the Regal was fitted with many amenities, including heated leather seats (optional on the Century), a [[Monsoon speakers|Monsoon]] 8-speaker surround sound system, dual climate control, and expansive interior space. Few changes occurred during this version's seven-year run. It offered 5-passenger seating on all trim levels like the Pontiac Grand Prix and Oldsmobile Intrigue (formerly Cutlass Supreme), unlike their predecessors that had optional 6-passenger seating and the Buick Century (formerly built on the [[GM A platform|A platform]]) which had standard 6-passenger seating.\n\nThis period held the fastest Buick since the days of the 1991\u20131996 Roadmaster, the Buick Regal GS. This car was now [[supercharged]] instead of turbocharged, and produced {{convert|240|hp|abbr=on|0}} and {{convert|280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. When introduced in January 1997,<ref>http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1996-08-11-9608110276-story.html</ref> Buick advertised the Regal GS as \"The official car of the supercharged family\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LoghkBiMmQk</ref> Buick also released two other model types, the LSE and the GSE. The LSE stayed with the {{convert|200|hp|abbr=on|0}} engine with upgrades and the GSE stayed with the {{convert|240|hp|abbr=on|0}} supercharged engine with upgrades. Also, in 2000 Buick came out with a concept GSX that had an intercooled 3.8&nbsp;L, but was supercharged rather than turbocharged. It had {{convert|295.24|hp|abbr=on}}\n\nThe North American Regal was replaced in 2005 by the [[Buick LaCrosse]], also built on the W platform. The final 2004 Buick Regal rolled off the assembly line on June 1, 2004.<ref name=\"Wards05\">{{cite book |title=Ward's Automotive Yearbook 2005 |publisher=Ward's Communications, Inc |year=2005 |page=112}}</ref>\n\n=== Engines ===\n* 1997\u20132004 [[GM 3800 engine#L36|3.8]]&nbsp;L L36 Series II [[V6]]\n* 1997\u20132004 [[GM 3800 engine#L67|3.8]]&nbsp;L L67 Series II supercharged [[V6]]\n\n=== Regal LS and GS performance ===\n[[File:Regal l67.jpg|thumb|left|The 3800 Series II L67 Supercharged engine in a 1998 GS]]\n\nThe Regal LS from the factory had a 1/4 mile (\u2248400 m) elapsed time (ET) of 15.8 seconds and could do 0-60&nbsp;mph in under 8 seconds. The supercharged Regal GS had a 1/4 mile ET of 14.9 seconds, and acceleration to {{convert|60|mi/h|km/h|0|abbr=on}} took 6.7 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |author=Albee Digital Communications |url=http://www.albeedigital.com/supercoupe/articles/0-60_Quarter_Mile_Times/B_0-60times.html |title=\"B\" 0-60 and 1/4 mile times for Factory Stock Vehicles |publisher=Albeedigital.com |accessdate=2009-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410163805/http://www.albeedigital.com/supercoupe/articles/0-60_Quarter_Mile_Times/B_0-60times.html |archivedate=2013-04-10 }}</ref>  The Regal GS, equipped with the supercharged 3.8 liter V6 engine (L67) produced {{convert|240|hp|abbr=on|0}} & {{convert|280|lb\u00b7ft|N.m|abbr=on}} of torque. The Regal GS's PCM has programming that activates torque management to reduce wheel spin at launch. The Regal LS was EPA rated at 19/30 MPG city/freeway while the supercharged Regal GS was EPA rated at 18/27 MPG city/freeway.\n\n=== Regal LSX and GSX (SLP Performance) ===\n[[File:Buick_Regal_GSX.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal GSX]]\nIn the 2003 and 2004 model years, Buick, in collaboration with SLP Performance, came out with the Buick Regal GSX. They offered dealer-installed options and dealer supplied accessories for both LS and GS models. Like the GS Buicks that came before it, the SLP GSX came in three power train packages, referred to as stages. The Stage 1 package added 10 horsepower with the addition of a dual stainless steel cat-back exhaust system and free-flowing cold air induction system. If you opted for the Stage 2 package, a Hypertech Power Programmer with an SLP custom calibration tune was included with the Stage 1 components \u2014 good for an extra 20 horsepower. The range-topping Stage 3 package added a 3.5-inch smaller diameter supercharger pulley to crank up the boost. With an advertised 30 more horsepower than stock, the Stage 3 GSX was conservatively rated at {{convert|270|hp|abbr=on|0}} and {{convert|312|lbft|abbr=on|0}} of torque. Since the parts were available from SLP over the counter for many years, there have been quite a few Regal GS sedans that have been cloned into a GSX for both appearance and performance purposes. Though the model didn\u2019t officially debut until 2003, a licensed SLP dealer could perform the transformation on any Regal GS from 1997 to 2004. A true GSX can be verified from an SLP door jamb label with the correct part number for the kit.<ref>https://www.cheatsheet.com/automobiles/buick-regal-gsx-it-lives-up-to-its-performance-heritage.html/</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fabini.com/slp/slpbuickgsx.html |title=SLP Buick Regal GSX |work=Fabini's Auto Trim Co |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710215458/http://www.fabini.com/slp/slpbuickgsx.html |archivedate=2011-07-10 }}</ref>\n\n===Joseph Abboud Edition===\nFrom 2001 to 2004 Buick offered a [[Joseph Abboud]] appearance package on both the GS and LS models. This package included either a solid [[taupe]] or two-tone taupe/[[Chestnut (color)|chestnut]] leather seats, two-tone leather wrapped steering wheel, leather shifter handle and boot, 16\" aluminum wheels; and Joseph Abboud signature emblems on the front doors, floor mats, front seat head rests, and taillights.\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:Buick Regal CN 01 China 2012-06-16.jpg|thumb|left|1999\u20132008 Buick Regal front quarter (China)]]\n[[File:Buick Regal CN 02 China 2012-06-16.jpg|thumb|right|1999\u20132008 Buick Regal rear quarter (China)]]\nGeneral Motors and [[Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation]] (SAIC) established a joint venture in 1997 called [[Shanghai GM]], and had begun assembling the Buick Regal in [[Shanghai]], [[People's Republic of China|China]] in April 1999.<ref name=china_0>{{cite web |url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1995%2C_GM_Links_with_SAIC |title=1995, GM Links with SAIC |year=2011 |work=history.gmheritagecenter.com |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z3cvAY0i?url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1995,_GM_Links_with_SAIC# |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=GM signed a milestone agreement with China\u2019s Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation (SAIC) for a proposed automotive joint venture, a joint venture technical center, and several other projects in and around the city of Shanghai... |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=globalization>{{cite web |url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1982_-1999,_Globalization,_One_Company,_One_Team |title=1982 -1999, Globalization, One Company, One Team |year=2011 |work=history.gmheritagecenter.com |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z3Uy5pg2?url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1982_-1999,_Globalization,_One_Company,_One_Team# |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=Also in 1995, the company entered into a joint venture agreement with Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation (SAIC) in China, laying the foundation for unprecedented growth over the next few years. Four years later, the Buick Regal was being assembled in China for the Chinese market... |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1999,_Buick_is_Back_in_Shanghai |title=1999, Buick is Back in Shanghai |year=2011 |work=history.gmheritagecenter.com |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z3V6i6Em?url=http://history.gmheritagecenter.com/wiki/index.php/1999,_Buick_is_Back_in_Shanghai# |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=The General Motors-SAIC joint venture plant in Shanghai began building Buick Regals for the Chinese market, marking the Buick brand\u2019s proud return to China. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Regal has sold well in the Chinese market as a large, relatively luxurious model, despite its high price, costing more than the North American version. The Chinese market Regal has different front- and rear-end styling compared to the North American version and different engines, including the 2.0&nbsp;L ''[[Family II engine#L34|L34]]'', the 2.5&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LB8|LB8]]'' V6 and the 3.0&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LW9|LW9]]'' V6. Gearbox choices were a 4-speed automatic for V6 models, while four-cylinder variants are paired with a 5-speed manual gearbox. V6 models had a set of black dashboard gauges, while the four-cylinder models had white dashboard gauges.  These models also had slightly different names: the entry-level model was the ''New Century'', with more upscale models carrying the ''GL'' and ''GLX'' names. Later, ''G'' and ''GS'' models were added. Production for this generation ended in November 2008 in China being replaced the Opel Insignia based Regal. The Chinese-built Regal was also sold in the Philippines from 2005 to 2008 as the Chevrolet Lumina, where it replaced the [[Opel Vectra]]. The 2.5 V6 was the only engine option.<ref>https://www.curbsideclassic.com/automotive-histories/obscure-rebadges-from-around-the-world-part-6/</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n== Fifth generation (2008) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Fifth generation\n| image = 2011 Buick Regal -- 07-04-2011.jpg\n| caption = 2011 Buick Regal CXL\n| aka = [[Opel Insignia]]<br />[[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] Insignia<br />[[Chevrolet]] Vectra<br />[[Holden]] Insignia\n| production = 2008\u20132017\n| model_years = China: 2009\u20132017<br /> North America: 2011\u20132017\n| assembly = [[People's Republic of China|China]]: November 2008\u20132017 ([[Shanghai General Motors]]) <br /> Germany: 2009\u2013February 2011 ([[Opel]] [[R\u00fcsselsheim]] Assembly)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoobserver.com/2011/09/sexy-opel-astra-gtc-could-be-next-new-buick.html|title=Sexy Opel Astra GTC Could Be Next New Buick|work=AutoObserver Sexy Opel Astra GTC Could Be Next New Buick}}</ref> <br /> Canada: [[Oshawa, Ontario]] February 2011\u20132017 ([[General Motors Canada]])\n| designer = Mark Adams (2006)<ref>https://www.motortrend.com/cars/buick/regal/2010/2010-buick-regal-drive/</ref> <br /> Malcolm Ward (2006)\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| platform = [[GM Epsilon II platform|Epsilon II]]\n| related = [[Buick LaCrosse]] <br /> [[Chevrolet Malibu]] <br /> [[Cadillac XTS]] <br /> [[Saab 9-5]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|FF layout]] / [[F4 layout]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list\n  |1.6 L ''[[GM Family 1 engine#Generation III|LLU]]'' [[Turbocharger|turbo]] [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (China Only)\n  |2.0 L ''LTD'' I4 (China Only)\n  |2.0 L ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LDK|LDK]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LHU|LHU]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' turbo I4\n  |2.4 L ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LE5|LE5]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LAF|LAF]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LEA|LEA]]/[[GM Ecotec engine#LUK|LUK]]'' I4\n}}\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list |6-speed [[Hydra-Matic]] ''[[GM 6T40 transmission|6T40]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|6-speed [[Hydra-Matic]] ''[[GM 6T50 transmission|6T50]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|6-speed [[Hydra-Matic]] ''[[GM 6T70 transmission|6T70]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]|6-speed [[Aisin Seiki Co.#Aisin AW|Aisin]] ''[[AWTF-80 SC|AF40]]'' automatic|6-speed [[Aisin]] ''[[GM F40|F40]]'' [[Manual transmission|manual]]}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|107.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|190.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|73.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|58.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{Convert|3600|lbs|abbr=on}} (2011 CXL) <br /> {{Convert|3671|lbs|abbr=on}} (2011 CXL Turbo)\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = [[Buick LaCrosse#First generation (2005\u20132009)|Buick LaCrosse]]\n| successor = \n}}\n\n{{See also|Opel Insignia}}\n[[File:Buick (12645920815).jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal]]\nThe fifth-generation Buick Regal is a four-door, five-passenger, [[Mid-size car|midsized]] [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] with a [[FF layout|front engine, front-wheel drive]] layout.<ref name=EPA_midsize>{{cite web |url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/2008car1tablef.jsp?id=30075 |title=2011 Buick Regal |year=2011 |work=fueleconomy.gov |publisher=United States Environmental Protection Agency |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4Zdiz4X?url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/2008car1tablef.jsp?id=30075 |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=Size Class Midsize Cars |url-status=dead }}</ref> GM says that the Regal is helping General Motors attract new, younger customers to the Buick brand. According to GM published information, more than 41% of Regal buyers in the US are coming from non-General Motors brands, and more than 60% of CXL Turbo buyers are under the age of 55.<ref name=gm_pr_110128>{{cite press release |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Jan/0128_regalturbo |title=Buick Regal Turbo Attracting New Customers to Brand |date=2011-01-28 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4fIzo1V?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Jan/0128_regalturbo |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=More than 60 percent of Regal Turbo customers alone are younger than 55, according to Power Information Network data. Since its launch last spring, 41 percent of Regal\u2019s buyers have come from non-GM brands. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Development ===\nThe fifth generation Buick Regal rides on GM's [[GM Epsilon II platform|Epsilon II]] platform and is mostly identical to the [[Opel Insignia]]. It first went into production in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Germany, in 2008.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/index.html |title=2011 Buick Regal |first=Todd |last=Lassa |date=November 2009 |work=motortrend.com |publisher=MotorTrend Magazine, Source Interlink Media |page=1 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4ZEcVDR?url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/specs.html |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=...GM planned to make the Opel Insignia Saturn's second-generation Aura. |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=regal_insignia>{{cite web |url=http://paultan.org/2008/11/05/new-buick-regal-for-china-based-on-insignia/ |title=New Buick Regal for China based on Insignia |first=Paul |last=Tan |date=2008-11-05 |work=Paul Tan's Automotive News |publisher=Driven Media Sdn Bhd |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z2AQjmKK?url=http://paultan.org/2008/11/05/new-buick-regal-for-china-based-on-insignia/ |archivedate=2011-05-29 |accessdate=2011-05-29 |quote=The new Opel Insignia (badged as a Vauxhall in the UK) is now in China, badged as a Buick. The Insignia is wearing the Buick Regal badge... |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[Shanghai GM]] twin of the Insignia was introduced in China as Buick Regal in December, 2008 for the 2009 model year.\n\nGM originally planned to sell a modified version of the Opel Insignia in North America as the second generation [[Saturn Aura]], but changed strategy after deciding to discontinue the [[Saturn Corporation|Saturn]] brand.<ref name=an_110508>{{cite web |url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110518/OEM04/110519901/1266 |title=Buick will get rebadged, redesigned Astra, report says |first=Rick |last=Kranz |date=2011-05-18 |work=autonews.com |publisher=Crain Communications, Inc |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z563fWtM?url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20110518%2FOEM04%2F110519901%2F1266 |archivedate=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=With Saturn's demise, Buick was selected to market a few rebadged Opel cars. For example, the current Insignia is marketed here as the Buick Regal, a key vehicle in the brand's turnaround. |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Regal utilizes [[Monocoque|unibody]] construction with [[galvanization|galvanized]] steel front fenders, hood, roof and door panels and [[Thermoplastic olefin|thermoplastic polyolefin]] (TPO) bumper covers.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p1\"/> The North American Regal weighs about {{Convert|13|lb|0|abbr=on}} more than an equivalent Opel Insignia due to increased structural support in the [[Pillar (car)|B-pillar]] necessary to meet U.S. [[Vehicle rollover|rollover]] standards.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/index.html|title=2011 Buick Regal|last=Lassa|first=Todd|date=November 2009|publisher=MotorTrend Magazine, Source Interlink Media|page=2|quote=The 2.4 comes with a GM Hydra-Matic 6T45 six-speed automatic, while the turbo comes with an Aisin AF40 six-speed automatic.|work=motortrend.com|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4VtdlaS?url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/engines.html|archivedate=2011-05-30|accessdate=2011-05-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing ===\nGM revealed the fifth generation Regal to North American dealers on October 14, 2009, and introduced the Regal to the public in November, 2009 at the [[LA Auto Show#2009|LA Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://archives.media.gm.com/archive/documents/domain_2/docId_57405_pr.html |title=Regal Named as Next Buick Sedan |date=2010-10-04 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4e8SLa1?url=http://archives.media.gm.com/archive/documents/domain_2/docId_57405_pr.html |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=...more than 1,000 dealers this week will be the first to learn the name of Buick\u2019s next mid-size sport sedan will be the Buick Regal. |url-status=dead }}</ref> Sales of the Regal began in February 2010. In North America, the Regal is positioned below the larger, more expensive [[Buick LaCrosse|LaCrosse]] and above the [[Buick Verano|Verano]] compact sedan which debuted late in calendar year 2011.\n\n=== Production ===\n[[File:Buick Regal CN II facelift China 2016-04-16.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal (China - facelift)]]\n\nProduction of the [[Shanghai GM]] variant of the Regal began in November 2008 and ended in July 2017. North American production at [[General Motors of Canada]]'s [[Oshawa, Ontario]], assembly plant was confirmed on November 25, 2009, and production began at [[Oshawa Car Assembly]] in February 2011.<ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25\"/><ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25-brand\"/> The initial production for the North American market was done together with its Opel twin the [[Opel Insignia]] in the [[Adam Opel AG]]'s [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Germany assembly plant from March 1, 2010 to March 25, 2011 (33,669 cars in 2010 and 12,637 in 2011).<ref name=\"Opel_FactFig2011\"/><ref name=\"Opel_Plant_display\">Production period according to a Foto on display at the Opel plant as seen on September 22, 2012, during the Open House on occasion of the 150-year Opel jubilee</ref>\n\n=== Trim levels ===\n\n==== {{anchor|CXL and CXL Turbo}} CXL ====\nThe Regal debuted in North America with a single engine, the 2.4L DOHC I4 engine and was rated at {{Convert|182|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|172|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque. The 2.4L engine is mated to a GM [[Hydramatic|Hydra-Matic]] 6T45 six-speed\n\nThe 2011 Regal produced in North America was offered in one trim level, called CXL, and was offered with two engine choices and seven option packages. Buick had planned to offer a lower-level trim called CX with cloth seats and a higher level trim called CXS, but those trim levels have not yet been offered.<ref name=\"mt_2011-09_p3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/future_plans.html |title=2011 Buick Regal |first=Todd |last=Lassa |date=November 2009 |work=motortrend.com |publisher=MotorTrend Magazine, Source Interlink Media |page=3 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4YVbINn?url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedans/112_0911_2011_buick_regal/future_plans.html |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=...Buick will add base, cloth-seat CX and high-zoot CXS trim levels. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== CXL Turbo ====\nThe CXL Turbo comes equipped with a [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] 2.0L direct-injected [[GM Ecotec engine|Ecotec]] DOHC I4 rated at {{Convert|220|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|258|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque, mated to either an [[Aisin Seiki Co.#Aisin AW|Aisin]] [[AWTF-80 SC|AF40]] 6-speed automatic or a 6-speed [[manual transmission]], making the Regal Turbo the first Buick model to be offered with a manual transmission since the [[Buick Skyhawk]] ended production in 1989. The 2.0L turbo is the first direct-injected turbocharged production car capable of running on any blend of gasoline or E85 ethanol.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/0221_regalturbo |title=Buick Regal Turbo Gets Industry-First Turbo Direct-Injected Engine with Flex-Fuel Capability |date=2011-02-21 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4gcFkpx?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/0221_regalturbo |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=The 2011 Buick Regal Turbo is the first direct-injected turbocharged production car capable of running on any blend of gasoline or E85 ethanol... |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== GS ====\n[[File:2011 Buick Verano (5490346021).jpg|thumb|left|2011 Buick Regal GS]]\nAt the [[North American International Auto Show#2010|2010 North American International Auto Show]] in Detroit, GM showed a concept GS version of the Regal based on the Opel Insignia [[Opel Performance Center|OPC]] and the Vauxhall Insignia VXR. The concept featured a 2.0L, {{convert|270|hp|0|abbr=on}}, {{convert|295|lbft|abbr=on}} high-output DOHC I4 turbocharged Ecotec engine, a 6-speed manual transmission and all-wheel drive.\n\nThe production GS leaves most of the concept specifications intact, but is front-wheel drive. The GS features Buick's Interactive Drive Control System with GS mode, a choice of an FGP Germany F40-6 six-speed manual or Aisin AF-40 (G2) six-speed automatic transmission, high performance brakes with [[Brembo]] front calipers and high performance strut (HiPerStrut) front suspension. 19&nbsp;inch wheels will be standard and 20&nbsp;inch forged aluminum wheels will be available. The GS is expected to accelerate from 0 to 60&nbsp;mph (97&nbsp;km/h) in under 7 seconds. The production version is equipped with GS-only high-output version of the Ecotec 2.0L turbo engine with {{Convert|270|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|295|lbft|abbr=on}} of torque. The GM LHU engine used in the GS trim makes 135&nbsp;hp per liter - Buick\u2019s highest specific output ever.<ref>{{cite web |last=Harman |first=Dan |title=Buick Regal |date=2014-02-05 |url=http://www.mojomotors.com/review/buick-regal/ |publisher=Mojo Motors |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NA6CL8No?url=http://www.mojomotors.com/review/buick-regal/ |archivedate=2014-02-05 |accessdate=2014-02-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The GS went on sale in fall 2011 as a 2012 model.<ref name=\"gm_pr_gs\">{{cite press release|title=Buick Regal GS Production Model Takes Sports Sedan Performance To A New Level For Buick|date=2010-11-04|publisher=General Motors Company|url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Nov/1104_gm_regal_gs|quote=Body style/driveline: four-door, five-passenger, front-engine transaxle. Front-wheel drive midsize sedan|accessdate=2011-05-30|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4bTpn44?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2010/Nov/1104_gm_regal_gs|archivedate=2011-05-30|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"cad_2010-04\">{{cite web |url=http://www.caranddriver.com/features/10q1/2012_buick_regal_gs-feature |title=2012 Buick Regal GS - Feature |date=April 2010 |work=caranddriver.com |publisher=Hachette Filipacchi Media U.S., Inc |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4cOkeJx?url=http://www.caranddriver.com/features/10q1/2012_buick_regal_gs-feature |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=While Europeans will get an Insignia OPC with a {{Convert|325|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}, turbocharged V-6, the GS gets a higher-output version of the 2.0-liter turbo four found in the Regal. |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Shanghai GM]] variant of Regal GS went on sale in China on September 15, 2011. This car has been localized. The output of the 2.0L Turbo SIDI engine is {{Convert|162|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}}, which is about {{Convert|40|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} less than the production US-model. The torque is {{convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}. and the top speed is claimed as {{convert|232|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}. The car is only offered in this case as a front-wheel-drive. There exist also some interior and exterior differences between the American and Chinese models.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buick.com.cn/RegalGS/ |title=2015\u6b3e\u65b0\u541b\u5a01GS \u7115\u65b0\u767b\u573a |publisher=Buick China |language=Chinese |date= |accessdate=2015-03-21}}</ref><ref name=shanghaigm_buick_gs>{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120131073541/http://buick.com.cn/RegalGS/specifications.aspx | url=http://www.buick.com.cn/RegalGS/specifications.aspx |title=\u522b\u514b\u5b98\u65b9\u7f51\u7ad9--\u541b\u5a01GS\u00b7\u667a\u9a71\u8c79-\u4ef7\u683c\u914d\u7f6e |publisher=Buick China | archivedate = 2012-01-31 | date= September 2011 | language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n==== Sport Touring Edition ====\nFor 2016, the Regal added a new Sport Touring Edition which included unique 18\" aluminum black pocket wheels and a rear lip spoiler.\n\n==== eAssist ====\n[[File:2012 Buick Regal eAssist WAS 2012 0830.JPG|thumb|2012 Buick Regal with optional [[BAS Hybrid#Generation II BAS (eAssist)|eAssist]] hybrid system]]\nBeginning in 2011, Buick began offering the [[BAS Hybrid#Generation II BAS (eAssist)|eAssist]] system in the Regal, The 2012 [[model year]] Regal is the second GM vehicle to offer eAssist after the 2012 [[Buick LaCrosse]]. The eAssist system is standard in the LaCrosse, but the eAssist powertrain is optional in the Regal.\n\nThe eAssist system adds a lithium-ion battery housed in the trunk, along with regenerative braking, engine stop/start, fuel cut-off, grille louvres that close at speed, underbody panels and low-rolling resistance tires. The eAssist system adds up to {{convert|15|hp|kW|abbr=on}} to the standard 2.4L Ecotec engine during acceleration. Fuel economy for the Regal with eAssist is estimated at {{convert|26|mpgus|abbr=on}} city, {{convert|37|mpgus|abbr=on}} highway.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/11chicago/buick/0208_Regal_eA |title=2012 Regal to Offer New eAssist\u2122 Fuel-Saving Technology |date=2011-02-08 |publisher=General Motors Company |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4n9b1i5?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2011/Feb/11chicago/buick/0208_Regal_eA |archivedate=2011-05-30 |accessdate=2011-05-30 |quote=Mated to Regal\u2019s 2.4L Ecotec direct injection four-cylinder engine and next-generation six-speed automatic transmission... |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 Update ===\n[[File:2014 Regal.JPG|thumb|2014 Buick Regal eAssist]]\nGM revealed an updated 2014 Regal at the [[New York Auto Show#2013|2013 New York Auto Show]]. Changes include a revised interior and exterior, a boost in performance for the CXL Turbo up to 258&nbsp;hp (192&nbsp;kW) and 295&nbsp;lb\u00b7ft (400 N\u00b7m) of torque, and an available all-wheel drive option offered for the 2.0L engine/6-speed automatic transmission equipped vehicles. Changes for the GS include revised interior and exterior, a drop in power to match that of the CXL Turbo, and available an all-wheel drive option offered for the 2.0L / six-speed automatic transmission equipped vehicles. The six-speed manual transmission is still offered, but only in the front-wheel drive variant. Buick's [[Buick#VentiPorts|VentiPorts]] have reappeared starting with 2014 models, a styling feature unique to Buick that dates back to 1949.\n\nSeveral new safety features were added for the 2014 year, which include forward collision warning, lane-departure warning, blind-spot monitoring, rear cross-traffic alert, and a following-distance indicator. The foregoing are all part of a Driver Confidence package, while collision preparation, which pre-loads the brake system ahead of an imminent collision, and adaptive cruise control are available separately.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamm|first=John|title=2014 Buick Regal / Regal GS|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/news/2014-buick-regal-photos-and-info-news|work=Car and Driver|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"6\" |Shanghai GM Regal Engines (Petrol)\n|-\n!Engine model\n!Type\n!Displacement\n!Power\n!Torque\n!Year\n|-\n![[GM Family 1 engine#Generation III|'''1.6T''']]\n| rowspan=\"5\" |I4\n|1,598 cc\n|{{Convert|179|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} at 5,800 rpm\n|{{Convert|220|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,200\u20135,400 rpm\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2008\u20132017\n|-\n![[GM Family II engine|2.0]]\n|1,998 cc\n|{{Convert|147|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} at 6,200 rpm\n|{{Convert|190|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 4,600 rpm\n|-\n![[GM Ecotec engine#LDK|2.0T SIDI]]\n|1,998 cc\n|220 PS (162&nbsp;kW; 218&nbsp;hp) at 5,300 rpm\n|{{Convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,000\u20134,000 rpm\n|-\n![[GM Ecotec engine#LE5|2.4]]\n|2,384 cc\n|170 PS (125&nbsp;kW; 168&nbsp;hp) at 6,400 rpm\n|{{Convert|225|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} at 4,800 rpm\n|2008\u20132010\n|-\n![[GM Ecotec engine#LAF|2.4 SIDI]]\n|2,384 cc\n|{{Convert|186|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} at 6,200 rpm\n|{{Convert|240|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 4,800 rpm\n|2011\u20132017\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Sixth generation (2018) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Sixth generation\n| image = 2018 Buick Regal Sportback Preferred II FWD, Ebony Twilight Metallic, front right.jpg\n| caption = 2018 Buick Regal Sportback\n| aka = {{unbulleted list|{{ill|\u522b\u514b\u541b\u5a01|zh|vertical-align=sup}} (Buick Regal; China)|[[Opel Insignia]] (Europe)|[[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]] Insignia (United Kingdom)|[[Holden Commodore (ZB)]] (Australia)}}\n| production = 2017\u2013present<!--Until production has stopped, production dates should be \"present\" - DO NOT change to \"2020\"-->\n| model_years = 2018\u2013present<br>2018\u2013present ([[North America]])<!--Until production has stopped, production dates should be \"present\" - DO NOT change to \"2020\"-->\n| assembly = [[Germany]]: [[R\u00fcsselsheim am Main|R\u00fcsselsheim]] ([[Opel Automobile GmbH]])<br/>[[China]]: [[Shanghai]] ([[SAIC-GM]])\n| designer = Mark Adams<br />Malcolm Ward\n| body_style = 4-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] (China only)<br/>5-door [[fastback]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cargurus.com/Cars/2018-Buick-Regal-Sportback-Overview-c27060|title=Review of New Buick Regal}}</ref> (sportback)<br/>5-door [[Station wagon|wagon]]<ref name=\"wagon\">{{cite web|title=2018 Buick Regal Wagon Confirmed During Dealer Meeting|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2016/05/2018-buick-regal-wagon-confirmed-during-dealer-meeting/|last=Szymkowski|first=Sean|website=GM Authority|date=May 30, 2016|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n| platform = [[GM Epsilon platform#E2XX|E2XX platform]]\n| related = {{unbulleted list|[[Buick LaCrosse]]|[[Chevrolet Malibu]]}}\n| layout = [[FF layout]] / [[F4 layout]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list\n  |1.5 L ''[[GM small gasoline engine#LFV|LFV]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] ([[turbocharger|turbo]]) (China only)\n  |1.8 L [[Straight-4|I4]] (hybrid gasoline/electric) (30H China only)\n  |2.0 L ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] (turbo)\n  |3.6 L ''[[GM High Feature engine#LGX|LGX]]'' [[V6]]\n}}\n| transmission = [[AWF8F35|AWF8F45]] (8-speed) (I4 [[All-wheel drive|AWD]])<br>GM 9-speed Hydramatic 9T65 (I4 [[Front-wheel drive|FWD]], V6 [[All-wheel drive|AWD]])<br>[[Continuously Variable Transmission|CVT]] (30H China only)\n| wheelbase = {{convert|111.4|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|192.7|in|mm|abbr=on}}<br />{{convert|196.4|in|mm|abbr=on}} (TourX)\n| width = {{convert|73.3|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|57.3|in|mm|abbr=on}}<br />{{convert|58.4|in|mm|abbr=on}} (TourX)\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n}}[[File:Buick Regal 2.0T IMG 20180417 111121.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal sedan, rear view|alt=]]On April 4, 2017, an all-new sixth generation Buick Regal was introduced at GM's Design Dome in [[Warren, Michigan]] as a 2018 model in both [[Hatchback|liftback]] and [[station wagon]] versions. Buick Regal began sales in China on July 21, 2017.<ref>[http://media.gm.com/media/cn/en/buick/vehicles/All-New-Buick-Regal/2017.html \"All-New Buick Regal\"], ''Buick News China'', Retrieved on 16 August 2017.</ref> Similar to the previous generation, it is related to the [[Opel Insignia|Opel and Vauxhall Insignia]] sold in Europe and [[Holden Commodore (ZB)|Holden ZB Commodore]] in Australia, and like the previous generation, the vehicles were developed and are produced by Opel in Germany.\n\n===Regal Sportback===\nThe [[fastback]] version of the Regal, now branded as Regal Sportback, is the replacement for the Regal sedan. While the roofline is similar to that of its predecessor, the new liftback configuration provides added utility. It has grown larger in size, and is around {{Convert|300-500|lb|0|abbr=on}} lighter than the previous Regal.<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Buick Regal Will Be Lighter, Longer Than Current Model|url=http://gmauthority.com/blog/2015/07/2017-buick-regal-will-be-lighter-longer-than-current-model/|last=Singer|first=Drew|website=GM Authority|date=July 30, 2016|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref> It carries two versions of the ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' 2.0 L [[Turbocharged]] [[inline-4]] engine. [[Front-wheel drive]] models produce {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5400 rpm and {{convert|260|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2000 rpm, while the [[all-wheel drive]] model produces {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5500 and {{convert|295|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3000 rpm, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Buick Regal spy shots|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1102584_2018-buick-regal-spy-shots|last=Vijayenthiran|first=Viknesh|website=Motor Authority|date=February 27, 2016|accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Regal TourX===\n[[File:Buick Regal TourX.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal TourX]]\n[[File:Buick Regal TourX rear.jpg|thumb|left|Rear view]]\nThe station wagon variant, named Regal TourX, was also introduced and went on sale at the same time as the hatchback, marking the first time since the demise of the [[Buick Roadmaster|Roadmaster]] in 1996 that Buick had a station wagon in its lineup. The TourX competes against the [[Volvo V60 Cross Country]], [[Audi A4 Allroad]], [[Subaru Outback]], and [[BMW 3 Series (F30)|BMW 3 Series wagon]], and offers up to 73.5 cubic feet of storage space behind the front seats, but only comes in all-wheel drive, along with a ''[[GM Ecotec engine#LTG|LTG]]'' turbocharged 2.0-liter four-cylinder producing an estimated {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|295|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} mated with an eight-speed automatic transmission.<ref name=\"wagon\" />\n\n===GS===\n[[File:Buick Regal II GS 001.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal GS sedan, front (China)]]\n[[File:Buick Regal II GS 002.jpg|thumb|left|Buick Regal GS sedan, rear (China)]]\nThe 2018 GS is the performance version of sixth generation Regal. This generation of GS sports a 3.6 liter [[GM High Feature engine|LGX]] V6 engine producing 310&nbsp;hp.\n\n===Discontinuation===\n\nIn December 2019, General Motors announced that it would end production of the Buick Regal for [[North America]] following the 2020 [[model year]], citing the popularity of the brand's [[sport utility vehicle]]s (SUV's), which have contributed to declining sales of Buick's passenger cars.  However, despite the discontinuation of the Regal in [[North America]], Buick will continue to produce the Regal for the [[China|Chinese]] market, where the vehicle recently received a mid-cycle facelift.<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2019/12/04/buick-regal-discontinued-gm-general-motors/2607182001/</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Sales ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Calendar year !! United States !! China !! Canada\n|-\n| 2009 || N/A || 80,401 || N/A\n|-\n| 2010 || 12,326 || 79,358 || 820\n|-\n| 2011 || 40,144 || 78,844 || 2,846\n|-\n| 2012 || 26,383 || 85,440 || 1,767\n|-\n| 2013 || 18,685 || 86,050 || 740\n|-\n| 2014 || 22,560 || 111,245 || 816\n|-\n| 2015 || 19,504 || 110,637 || 968\n|-\n| 2016 || 19,833 || 69,300 || 841\n|-\n| 2017 || 11,559 || 61,619 || 662\n|-\n| 2018 || 14,118 || 100,378 ||\n|-\n| 2019 || 10,363 || 123,587 ||\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Buick Gran Sport]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25\">{{cite press release \n |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |title=2011 Buick Regal to be built at the Oshawa Car Assembly Plant \n |date=2009-11-25 \n |publisher=General Motors Company \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4hXxaae?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/gm/news.detail.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |archivedate=2011-05-30 \n |accessdate=2011-05-30 \n |quote=North American production of the all-new 2011 Buick Regal was today confirmed for the Oshawa Car Assembly plant beginning in Q1 2011. \n |url-status=dead \n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"mediaGM_2009-11-25-brand\">{{cite press release \n |url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |title=2011 Buick Regal to be built at the Oshawa Car Assembly Plant \n |publisher=GM Media Online \n |date=2009-11-25 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z26fCY4m?url=http://media.gm.com/content/media/us/en/news/news_detail.brand_gm.html/content/Pages/news/us/en/2009/Nov/1125_GM_Buick_Regal \n |archivedate=2011-05-29 \n |accessdate=2011-05-28 \n |url-status=dead \n }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Opel_FactFig2011\">{{cite web \n|url= http://mediaassets.gmeuropearchive.info//ispace/pr/download/FactsFigures2011_www.pdf \n|title=Opel Facts and Figures 2011|page=34|author=Opel Corporate Communications\n|work=media.opel.com |date=February 2012\n|accessdate=20 September 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.gm.ca/gm/english/vehicles/buick/regal/overview Buick Regal official website - Canada]\n*[http://www.buick.com/regal-luxury-sport-sedan.html Buick Regal Official US Website]\n\n{{Buick Vehicles}}\n{{Buick postwar timeline}}\n{{Buick}}\n{{Buick China timeline}}\n\n[[Category:Buick vehicles|Regal]]\n[[Category:Flexible-fuel vehicles]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Mid-size cars]]\n[[Category:Sports sedans]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1973]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:2020s cars]]\n[[Category:Personal luxury cars]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:1528:436f:141e:5482:ea65:5a94", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFifth generation (2008))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buick_Regal"}
{"title_page": "Ernest Delahaye", "text_new": "[[Image:Ernest Delahaye.jpg|thumb|Delahaye, anonymous photograph, about 1890.]]\n'''Ernest Delahaye''' (1853\u20131930) was a French writer and essayist. He maintained a long and close friendship with [[Arthur Rimbaud]] with whom he first met in April 1865 when they attended school together in [[Charleville-M\u00e9zi\u00e8res|Charleville]] in the Ardennes region of France.{{sfn|Robb|2000|pp=23-25}}{{sfn|Starkie|1973|pp=20-21}} He and Rimbaud had a shared interest in poetry, and he would help Rimbaud by making fair copies of his drafts for distribution to Rimbaud's literary friends. He was one of the few (seven) recipients of the privately printed [[A Season in Hell]]{{sfn|Robb|2001|p=233|ps=: Rimbaud gave the others to his mother, [[Paul Verlaine]], [[Raoul Ponchon]], [[Jean-Louis Forain]], [[Jean Richepin]] and Ernest Millot.}} though Rimbaud later asked for it back to give it to someone else.{{sfn|Robb|2000|p=235}}{{sfn|Nicholl|1999|p=72|ps=: A widow in Milan}} According to Rimbaud biographer, [[Charles Nicholl (author)|Charles Nicholl]], Rimbaud's \"[last] strictly dateable poem\" was contained in a letter to Delahaye of 14 October 1875.{{sfn|Nicholl|1999|p=73}} Through Rimbaud, Delahaye also met poet [[Paul Verlaine]] and became friendly with him. Verlaine wrote a poem - ''Sonnet Boiteux'' - which is dedicated to him. Delahaye mixed his civil service career, working at the Education Ministry,{{sfn|Robb|2000|pp=430}} with writing biographical material on both Rimbaud and Verlaine, contributing first-hand accounts of the poets' lives and families.{{sfn|White|2008|pp=25-26}} Most of Delahaye's correspondence with Rimbaud and Verlaine survives.\n\n== Works ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation| last = Delahaye| first = Ernest | authorlink= Ernest Delahaye | origyear = 1919 | year = 1974 | title = Delahaye, t\u00e9moin de Rimbaud | language = French | publisher = La Baconni\u00e8re | location = Geneva | isbn = 978-2825200711 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Citation| last = Delahaye| first = Ernest | authorlink= Ernest Delahaye | origyear = | year = 2007 | title = Rimbaud; l'artiste et l'\u00eatre moral | language = French | publisher = Cerf | location = Paris | isbn = 978-2204083447 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Citation| last1 = Delahaye| first1 = Ernest | authorlink1= Ernest Delahaye | last2 = Vecchiet | first2 = Jean-Michel | origyear =  | year = 2010 | title = Mon ami Rimbaud | language = French | publisher = Editions Na\u00efve | location = Paris | isbn = 978-2350212159 | ref = harv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==References ==\n\n{{Empty section|date=December 2015}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation| last = Lefr\u00e8re | first = Jean-Jacques| year =2001| title =Arthur Rimbaud | language = French | location = Paris | publisher = Fayard | isbn = 978-2-213-60691-0 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Citation| last = Lefr\u00e8re | first = Jean-Jacques | year =2007| title =Correspondance de Rimbaud | language = French | location = Paris | publisher = Fayard | isbn = 978-2-213-63391-6 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Citation | last = Nicholl | first = Charles | authorlink = Charles Nicholl (author) | year = 1999 | title = Somebody Else: Arthur Rimbaud in Africa 1880\u201391 | location = Chicago | publisher = University of Chicago Press | isbn = 0-226-58029-6 | ref = harv | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/somebodyelsearth00nich }}\n* {{Citation| last=Robb | first=Graham | authorlink=Graham Robb | year=2000 | title= Rimbaud | publisher= W.W. Norton & Co | location=New York | isbn =978-0330482820 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation| last=Starkie | first=Enid | authorlink=Enid Starkie | year=1973 | title=Arthur Rimbaud | publisher = Faber and Faber | location=London | isbn =0-571-10440-1 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation| last=White | first= Edmund | authorlink= Edmund White | year = 2008 | title = Rimbaud: The Double Life of a Rebel | location = London | publisher = Grove | isbn = 978-1-84354