etition | Intercontinental Cup }}\n{{MedalGold | 2012 Huangshi |Singles <ref name=\"IntercontinentalCup\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story2.asp?ID=29251&Category= |title=Runner Up in Singapore, Winner in Huangshi, Ariel Hsing Flies High |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 19, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]] | [[Table tennis at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's team|Team]]<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |title=XVI Pan-American Games Results Book |url=http://www.ittf.com/juniors/2011/Guadalajara_PANAM_Games/XVI_PANAMGAMES_resultsbook.pdf |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=3 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315034943/http://www.ittf.com/juniors/2011/Guadalajara_PANAM_Games/XVI_PANAMGAMES_resultsbook.pdf |archivedate=March 15, 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]] | [[Table tennis at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's singles|Singles]]<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> }}\n{{MedalCompetition | North American Championships }}\n{{MedalGold | 2013 Vancouver |Singles<ref name=\"NAChamps\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?Year=&General_Catigory=&ID=32721&Category=&Competition_ID=&Player_ID=111120& |title=Revenge is Sweet for Ariel Hsing; Top Seeds Capture North American Titles |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 19, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n{{MedalCompetition | North America Cup }}\n{{MedalGold | 2012 Mississauga |Singles<ref name=\"NACup2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?ID=28123&Competition_ID=2155& |title=Graduation Day, Teenagers Capture ITTF-North American Cup Titles |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 17, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Mississauga |Singles<ref name=\"NACup\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?ID=23868&Competition_ID=2031& |title=Ariel Hsing Secures ITTF-North America Cup Crown in Resounding Style |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 17, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n}}\n\n{{chinese|title=Ariel Yenhua Hsing|t={{linktext|\u90a2|\u5ef6|\u83ef}}|s={{linktext|\u90a2|\u5ef6|\u534e}}|p=X\u00edng Y\u00e1nhu\u00e1|w=Hsing<sup>2</sup> Yen<sup>2</sup>-hua<sup>2</sup>}}\n\n'''Ariel Yenhua Hsing''' (born November 29, 1995)<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/hs/ariel-hsing-1.html |title=Ariel Hsing |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> is an American [[table tennis]] player who competed in the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].\n\nHsing became the youngest U.S. table tennis national champion in history in 2010 at age 15. She repeated as champion in 2011 and 2013. She is the first player from North America to win the Intercontinental Cup<ref name= IntercontinentalCup /> in 2012 with participants from Africa, Latin America, North America, and Oceania.\n\nShe was a [[bronze medal]]ist in women's team and women's singles at the [[Table tennis at the 2011 Pan American Games|2011 Pan American Games]]. Hsing was the women's singles champion at the North American Championships in the year 2013,<ref name= NAChamps /> and at the North America Cup in the year 2011<ref name= NACup /> and 2012.<ref name= NACup2 /> During her junior career, she was ranked as high as 4th in the world in both the cadet (U-15)<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF U-15 World Ranking |url=http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=0&U21=0&Siniors=0& |accessdate=26 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828024656/http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=0&U21=0&Siniors=0& |archivedate=August 28, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the junior (U-18)<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF U-18 World Ranking |url=http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=1&U21=0&Siniors=0& |accessdate=26 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304102133/http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=1&U21=0&Siniors=0& |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> age group.\n\nIn May 2014, she became the first American-born player in the [[China Table Tennis Super League]], signing a contract with Zhejiang Jinhua Bank.<ref>{{in lang|zh}} [http://epaper.jhnews.com.cn/site1/jhrb/html/2014-06/01/content_1805823.htm \u9996\u4f4d\u5f15\u8fdb\u4e52\u8d85\u7684\u7f8e\u56fd\u7403\u5458\u90a2\u5ef6\u534e] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223736/http://epaper.jhnews.com.cn/site1/jhrb/html/2014-06/01/content_1805823.htm |date=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nHsing was born in [[Fremont, CA|Fremont]], [[California]], in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. Her mother, Xin Hua Jiang, was born in [[Mainland China|China]], and grew up in [[Henan Province]]. Her father, Michael Hsing, is a computer engineer who was born in [[Taiwan]].<ref name=\"family\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/table-tennis/hsing-advances-to-second-round.html |title=Hsing advances to second round |last=Wade |first=Stephen |date=July 28, 2012 |work=NBC Olympics |accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Almond, Elliott |title=The Bay Area's little-known table tennis mecca |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_21014290/bay-areas-little-known-table-tennis-mecca |newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]]  |date=July 5, 2012 |accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHsing started playing table tennis when her parents could not find a babysitter one night and brought the then seven-year-old to the [[Palo Alto]] Table Tennis Club with them.<ref name=\"teamusa.org\">{{cite web |title=Ariel Hsing |url=http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/HS/Ariel-Hsing |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> She joined the Palo Alto Table Tennis Club junior training program under the head coach Dennis Davis.\n\nAriel played her first table tennis tournament \u201c2003 California Open\u201d at age 7. She didn't quite know how to serve legally and was faulted more than ten times. She hung in there and won her first tournament.\n\nAt age eight and a few days old, Ariel won her first national title \u201cGirls 10 and Under\u201d at the 2003 U.S. Nationals at Las Vegas. She then successfully defended her title in 2004 and 2005. On a side note, Ariel's mom also won a trophy at the same tournament.\n\nIn July 2005, Ariel won all her matches at the 2005 Junior Olympics/Nationals held at New Orleans. She brought home six gold medals and a special \u201cJoel Ferrell Sportsmanship Award,\u201d which had her name engraved on a special plaque at the AAU (Amateur Athletic Union) National Headquarter.\n\n==Career==\nIn 2012, Hsing won the singles titles at the ITTF North American Cup and the United States Junior and Cadet Open.<ref name=\"titlecollection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story.asp?ID=28422&Category= |title=Ariel Hsing |last=Marshall |first=Ian |date=July 5, 2012 |work=ITTF |accessdate=July 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071151/http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story.asp?ID=28422&Category= |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> She qualified for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and was seeded 46th in women's singles.<ref name=\"2012 seeds\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/World_Events/2012OG/2012_OG_W_Singles_Seeding.pdf |title=2012 Olympic Games: Women\u2019s Singles Seeding List |work=International Table Tennis Federation |accessdate=July 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731210337/http://www.ittf.com/World_Events/2012OG/2012_OG_W_Singles_Seeding.pdf |archivedate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHsing is acquaintances with [[Warren Buffett]] and [[Bill Gates]] and used to refer to them as \"Uncle Warren\" and \"Uncle Bill\". She met Buffett at age 9 when one of Buffett's friends retained a table tennis coach for Buffett at his seventy-fifth birthday party and it was decided to have the 9-year-old Hsing play Buffett as a joke.<ref name=\"buffett\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/tabletennis/story/2012-07-01/Ariel-Hsing-Bill-Gates-Warren-Buffett/55997800/1 |title=Ariel Hsing is table tennis prodigy with influential fans |last=Florek |first=Michael |date=July 3, 2012 |work=USA Today |accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/video/warren-buffett-olympic-discovery/C79C0DFF-3687-4894-AFD2-047AFC2E12DB.html |title=Warren Buffett's Olympic Discovery |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=May 3, 2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> Since then, Ariel has been invited to the Berkshire Hathaway Annual Shareholders Meeting to play table tennis with Warren Buffett, Bill Gates, and the stockholders.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.omaha.com/money/warren-buffett-and-bill-gates-try-their-hand-at-table/article_93382bf4-f1eb-11e4-a076-83613e06e61b.html |title=Warren Buffett and Bill Gates try their hand at table tennis |newspaper=[[Omaha World-Herald]] |date=May 4, 2015 |accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> Gates was present during Hsing's Round of 32 loss during the 2012 Olympics and hugged her as she left the court.<ref name=\"2012 World Rankings\" />\n\nOn July 9, 2012, she appeared on an episode of the [[Nickelodeon]] [[game show]] ''[[Figure It Out]]''. She stumped panelists [[Ciara Bravo]], [[Alex Heartman]], [[Leon Thomas III]] and [[Stephen Kramer Glickman]], for one round.\n\n== 2012 London Olympics ==\n[[File:Ariel Hing in London 2012.jpg|thumb|Ariel Hing in London during the 2012 Olympics]]\n\nHsing entered the Olympics as the 46th seed <ref name=\"2012 seeds\" /> and ranked 115th in the world.<ref name=\"2012 World Rankings\">{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Toby |title=Gates flies in to hail \"amazing\" Hsing |url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/table-tennis/gates-flies-in-to-hail-amazing-hsing.html |work=NBC Olympics |accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the round of 128 Hsing defeated [[Yadira Silva]] in 4 games (11-9, 11\u20138, 11\u20133, 11-5) in a match where she never trailed by more than 2 points.\nIn the round of 64 Hsing defeated [[Ni Xia Lian]] of Luxembourg 4-2 (11-9, 10\u201312, 11\u20139, 11\u20135, 10\u201312, 12-10),\nIn the round of 32 Hsing lost to the #2 seed and eventual gold medalist [[Li Xiaoxia]] of China 4-2 (11-4, 9-11, 11\u20136, 6-11, 11\u20138, 11-9) with the longest rally of 18 occurring in game 6.\n\nAfter the loss Hsing said it was the best she had ever performed at a tournament giving herself a \"10 out of 10, or maybe 9.9 as I wasn't quite there.\"<ref name=\"2012 World Rankings\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nHsing has been blogging for espnW for her Olympic journey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/athletes-life/article/7558315/ariel-hsing-hopes-training-take-olympics |title=Hsing hopes training will take her to Olympics |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=February 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Olympics, Hsing was selected as the 2012 Female High School Athlete of the year by San Jose Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vcs.net/cf_news/view.cfm?newsid=273 |title=Ariel Hsing to be Honored by San Jose Sports Authority as Female Athlete of the Year |publisher=vcs.net |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHsing graduated from [[Valley Christian High School (San Jose, California)|Valley Christian High School]] in [[San Jose, CA|San Jose]] in 2013. She is a graduate of [[Princeton University]]<ref>Rolston, Dorian [http://paw.princeton.edu/issues/2014/02/05/pages/7604/index.xml \"Bullwhip backhands: A national champion as a freshman, Hsing looks to another Olympic run\"] ''Princeton Alumni Weekly'', February 5, 2014</ref> and was elected as Social Chair for the Class of 2017. Hsing speaks both [[English language|English]] and [[Mandarin Chinese]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Purdy, Mark |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_21188835/mark-purdy-san-joses-ariel-hsing-makes-most |title=Mark Purdy: San Jose's Ariel Hsing makes most of her Olympic moments at London Games |newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]] |date=July 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe is featured in the documentary ''[[Top Spin (documentary)|Top Spin]]'' directed by Mina T. Son and Sara Newens.\n\nAriel participated in Andy Akiho's Ping Pong Concerto, world premiered in Shanghai on July 18, 2015, at Shanghai Symphony Hall by [[Shanghai Symphony Orchestra]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.camimusic.com/news-blog/2015/11/9/shanghai-symphony-orchestra-world-premiered-ping-pong-concerto-ricochet-on-music-in-the-summer-air-misa-festival |title=Shanghai Symphony Orchestra world premiered Ping Pong Concerto (RICOCHET) on Music in the Summer Air (MISA) Festival |newspaper=Cami Music |access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref> Ping Pong Concerto has also performed in Beijing, Guangzhou, Foshan, and is scheduled to perform in London and Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hkphil.org/eng/concerts_and_ticket/concerts/concertdetail.jsp?id=570 |title=Ping Pong Diplomacy - Hong Kong Philharmonic |publisher=HKPhil |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAriel is a contributing author of \"2 Billion Under 20: How Millennials Are Breaking Down Age Barriers and Changing the World\" by [[Stacey Ferreira]] and Jared Kleinert, which became the #1 New Release in Business Leadership on Amazon.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Billion-Under-20-Millennials-Breaking/dp/1250067618 |title=2 Billion Under 20: How Millennials Are Breaking Down Age Barriers and Changing the World |publisher=amazon |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, with her independent study of \"Chinese Stock Market Anomalies: An Empirical Analysis,\u201d Ariel was selected by China Hands Magazine as the 25 under 25: Leaders in U.S.-China Relations, which \"profiles 25 students and professionals under the age of 25 who have demonstrated exceptional promise in China studies and in furthering the future of the U.S.-China relationship.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://chinahandsmagazine.org/2017/01/17/2016-25-under-25-leaders-in-u-s-china-relations/amp/ |title=2016 25 Under 25: Leaders in U.S.-China Relations |publisher=chinahandsmag |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Competition records<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialarielhsing.com/ariels-milestones/ |title=ARIEL\u2019S MILESTONES |publisher=officialarielhsing.com |accessdate=January 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235934/http://www.officialarielhsing.com/ariels-milestones/ |archive-date=February 1, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>==\n\n*2015 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Team Champion (Princeton University)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/article/2015/04/table-tennis-triumphs-at-nationals |title=Table tennis triumphs at Nationals |publisher=dailyprincetonian.com |accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n*2015 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Doubles Champion\n*2014 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Team Champion (Princeton University)\n*2014 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Singles Champion\n*2013 North American Championship \u2013 Women's Singles Champion\n*2013 North American Championship \u2013 Junior Girls' Team Champion\n*2013 North American Championship \u2013 Junior Girls' Singles Champion\n*2013 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles, Mixed Doubles, Women's U21-Silver  \n*2012 ITTF Intercontinental Cup \u2013 Women's Champion\n*2012 North America Cup \u2013 Women's Champion\n*2012 ITTF Brazil Open \u2013 Women's U21 Champion\n*2012 ITTF USA Junior & Cadet Open \u2013 Junior Girls Singles, Doubles, and Team Champions.\n*2011 North American Championship and Cup Women's Champion\n*2011 ITTF Junior Circuit Finals \u2013 Girls Singles 3rd place.\n*2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women Team Bronze medalist\n*2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women Singles Bronze medalist\n*2011 JUIC International Jr. & Cadet \u2013  Open Champion\n*2011 Canadian Junior Open \u2013  Team and doubles Champion, Single 2nd\n*2010 ITTF Global Cadet Challenge \u2013 Girls Single 3rd place\n*2010 ITTF Global Cadet Challenge \u2013 Girls Doubles 2nd place\n*2010 Inaugural Youth Olympic Games \u2013 USA representative\n*2010 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2010 North America Championship \u2013 Junior Girls 2nd place\n*2010 North America Championship Junior Girls Team Champion\n*2010 China vs. World Team Challenge \u2013 Represented Junior Girls World team finished 2nd place.\n*2010 Italian Junior & Cadet Open \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles Champion\n*2010 Italian Junior & Cadet Open \u2013 Cadet Girls Doubles Champion\n*2010 Safir International \u2013 Girls Under 16 Champion\n*2010 PanAm Youth Olymplics Trial in El Salvador \u2013 Girls First Place\n*2009 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2009 North America Championship \u2013 Junior Girls singles Champion\n*2009 North America Championship Junior Girls Team Champion\n*2009 Pan American ITTF Cadet Challenge Trial Champion\n*2009 Canadian Junior open Cadet Champion\n*2009 Canadian Junior open Cadet Doubles Champion\n*2009 Canadian Junior open Junior Team Champion\n*2008 Pan American Junior Girls champion\n*2008 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2008 North America Championship \u2013 Junior Girls singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Junior Girls Singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and Under Singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and under Singles Champion\n*2007 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2007 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Team Champion\n*2006 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and Under Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 15 and under Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and under Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 11 and under Singles Champion\n*2005 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles 2nd place\n*2005 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girl 10 and under Singles Champion\n*2005 Junior National under 10 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior National under 12 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior National under 14 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior Olympic under 10 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior Olympic under 12 Girl double: Gold\n*2005 Junior Olympic team under 16 girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior National/Olympic Joel Ferrell Sportsmanship Award\n*2004 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girl 10 and under Singles Champion\n*2003 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girl 10 and under Singles Champion\n\n== References ==\n[[File:Ariel Hsing.jpg|right|thumb|Hsing playing at the 2007 [[Berkshire Hathaway]] shareholders meeting in [[Omaha, Nebraska]], USA.]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ITTF|111120}}\n** {{Cite web |url=http://www.ittfranking.com/cgi-bin/ttplayer.cgi?number=111120&lang=0&format=summary |title=Ariel Hsing at ittfranking.com |access-date=June 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719111711/http://www.ittfranking.com/cgi-bin/ttplayer.cgi?number=111120&lang=0&format=summary |archive-date=July 19, 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown }}\n* {{IOC profile|ariel-hsing}}\n* {{USOC profile|HS/Ariel-Hsing}}\n\n{{Footer North American Champions Table Tennis Singles Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hsing, Ariel}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female table tennis players]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Olympic table tennis players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Fremont, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Alameda County, California]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2011 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of Northern Han Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in table tennis]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Xing (surname)|Hsing]]}}\n{{Infobox table tennis player\n| name             = Ariel Hsing\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Hsing won Women's Singles, Doubles, and Mixed Doubles at 2013 U.S. Nationals\n| fullname         = Ariel Yenhua Hsing<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/ittf_stats/All_events3.asp?ID=10584&From=1926&To=&s_EVENTS=NAC&s_Evnt=S&s_Gender=Female&s_gender2=& |title=ITTF_Database \u2013 HSING Ariel Yenhua (USA) |publisher=Ittf.com |accessdate=2014-06-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603020847/http://www.ittf.com/ittf_stats/All_events3.asp?ID=10584&From=1926&To=&s_EVENTS=NAC&s_Evnt=S&s_Gender=Female&s_gender2=& |archivedate=June 3, 2015 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| club             = Jinhua Bank ([[China Table Tennis Super League|China]])\n| nationality      = American\n| playingstyle     = Shakehand\n| hrank            = 73 (October 2012)<ref name=\"ITTF ranking\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=0&U21=0&Siniors=1& |title=ITTF world ranking |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=2012-10-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817100323/http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=0&U21=0&Siniors=1& |archivedate=August 17, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1995|11|29}}\n| birth_place      = [[Fremont, California]]<ref name=\"sports-reference\" />\n| residence        = [[San Jose, California]]<ref name=\"sports-reference\" />\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| height           = {{convert|5|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"sports-reference\" />\n| weight           = {{convert|117|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"sports-reference\" />\n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Women's [[table tennis]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | Intercontinental Cup }}\n{{MedalGold | 2012 Huangshi |Singles <ref name=\"IntercontinentalCup\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story2.asp?ID=29251&Category= |title=Runner Up in Singapore, Winner in Huangshi, Ariel Hsing Flies High |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 19, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]] | [[Table tennis at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's team|Team]]<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |title=XVI Pan-American Games Results Book |url=http://www.ittf.com/juniors/2011/Guadalajara_PANAM_Games/XVI_PANAMGAMES_resultsbook.pdf |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=3 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315034943/http://www.ittf.com/juniors/2011/Guadalajara_PANAM_Games/XVI_PANAMGAMES_resultsbook.pdf |archivedate=March 15, 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]] | [[Table tennis at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's singles|Singles]]<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> }}\n{{MedalCompetition | North American Championships }}\n{{MedalGold | 2013 Vancouver |Singles<ref name=\"NAChamps\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?Year=&General_Catigory=&ID=32721&Category=&Competition_ID=&Player_ID=111120& |title=Revenge is Sweet for Ariel Hsing; Top Seeds Capture North American Titles |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 19, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n{{MedalCompetition | North America Cup }}\n{{MedalGold | 2012 Mississauga |Singles<ref name=\"NACup2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?ID=28123&Competition_ID=2155& |title=Graduation Day, Teenagers Capture ITTF-North American Cup Titles |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 17, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Mississauga |Singles<ref name=\"NACup\">{{cite web |url=http://www.old.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?ID=23868&Competition_ID=2031& |title=Ariel Hsing Secures ITTF-North America Cup Crown in Resounding Style |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=January 17, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> }}\n}}\n\n{{chinese|title=Ariel Yenhua Hsing|t={{linktext|\u90a2|\u5ef6|\u83ef}}|s={{linktext|\u90a2|\u5ef6|\u534e}}|p=X\u00edng Y\u00e1nhu\u00e1|w=Hsing<sup>2</sup> Yen<sup>2</sup>-hua<sup>2</sup>}}\n\n'''Ariel Yenhua Hsing''' (born November 29, 1995)<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/hs/ariel-hsing-1.html |title=Ariel Hsing |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> is an American [[table tennis]] player who competed in the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].\n\nHsing became the youngest U.S. table tennis national champion in history in 2010 at age 15. She repeated as champion in 2011 and 2013. She is the first player from North America to win the Intercontinental Cup<ref name= IntercontinentalCup /> in 2012 with participants from Africa, Latin America, North America, and Oceania.\n\nShe was a [[bronze medal]]ist in women's team and women's singles at the [[Table tennis at the 2011 Pan American Games|2011 Pan American Games]]. Hsing was the women's singles champion at the North American Championships in the year 2013,<ref name= NAChamps /> and at the North America Cup in the year 2011<ref name= NACup /> and 2012.<ref name= NACup2 /> During her junior career, she was ranked as high as 4th in the world in both the cadet (U-15)<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF U-15 World Ranking |url=http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=0&U21=0&Siniors=0& |accessdate=26 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828024656/http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=0&U21=0&Siniors=0& |archivedate=August 28, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the junior (U-18)<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF U-18 World Ranking |url=http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=1&U21=0&Siniors=0& |accessdate=26 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304102133/http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=111120&U18=1&U21=0&Siniors=0& |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> age group.\n\nIn May 2014, she became the first American-born player in the [[China Table Tennis Super League]], signing a contract with Zhejiang Jinhua Bank.<ref>{{in lang|zh}} [http://epaper.jhnews.com.cn/site1/jhrb/html/2014-06/01/content_1805823.htm \u9996\u4f4d\u5f15\u8fdb\u4e52\u8d85\u7684\u7f8e\u56fd\u7403\u5458\u90a2\u5ef6\u534e] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223736/http://epaper.jhnews.com.cn/site1/jhrb/html/2014-06/01/content_1805823.htm |date=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nHsing was born in [[Fremont, CA|Fremont]], [[California]], in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. Her mother, Xin Hua Jiang, was born in [[Mainland China|China]], and grew up in [[Henan Province]]. Her father, Michael Hsing, is a computer engineer who was born in [[Taiwan]].<ref name=\"family\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/table-tennis/hsing-advances-to-second-round.html |title=Hsing advances to second round |last=Wade |first=Stephen |date=July 28, 2012 |work=NBC Olympics |accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Almond, Elliott |title=The Bay Area's little-known table tennis mecca |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_21014290/bay-areas-little-known-table-tennis-mecca |newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]]  |date=July 5, 2012 |accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHsing started playing table tennis when her parents could not find a babysitter one night and brought the then seven-year-old to the [[Palo Alto]] Table Tennis Club with them.<ref name=\"teamusa.org\">{{cite web |title=Ariel Hsing |url=http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/HS/Ariel-Hsing |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> She joined the Palo Alto Table Tennis Club junior training program under the head coach Dennis Davis.\n\nAriel played her first table tennis tournament \u201c2003 California Open\u201d at age 7. She didn't quite know how to serve legally and was faulted more than ten times. She hung in there and won her first tournament.\n\nAt age eight and a few days old, Ariel won her first national title \u201cGirls 10 and Under\u201d at the 2003 U.S. Nationals at Las Vegas. She then successfully defended her title in 2004 and 2005. On a side note, Ariel's mom also won a trophy at the same tournament.\n\nIn July 2005, Ariel won all her matches at the 2005 Junior Olympics/Nationals held at New Orleans. She brought home six gold medals and a special \u201cJoel Ferrell Sportsmanship Award,\u201d which had her name engraved on a special plaque at the AAU (Amateur Athletic Union) National Headquarter.\n\n==Career==\nIn 2012, Hsing won the singles titles at the ITTF North American Cup and the United States Junior and Cadet Open.<ref name=\"titlecollection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story.asp?ID=28422&Category= |title=Ariel Hsing |last=Marshall |first=Ian |date=July 5, 2012 |work=ITTF |accessdate=July 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071151/http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story.asp?ID=28422&Category= |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> She qualified for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and was seeded 46th in women's singles.<ref name=\"2012 seeds\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/World_Events/2012OG/2012_OG_W_Singles_Seeding.pdf |title=2012 Olympic Games: Women\u2019s Singles Seeding List |work=International Table Tennis Federation |accessdate=July 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731210337/http://www.ittf.com/World_Events/2012OG/2012_OG_W_Singles_Seeding.pdf |archivedate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHsing is acquaintances with [[Warren Buffett]] and [[Bill Gates]] and used to refer to them as \"Uncle Warren\" and \"Uncle Bill\". She met Buffett at age 9 when one of Buffett's friends retained a table tennis coach for Buffett at his seventy-fifth birthday party and it was decided to have the 9-year-old Hsing play Buffett as a joke.<ref name=\"buffett\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/london/tabletennis/story/2012-07-01/Ariel-Hsing-Bill-Gates-Warren-Buffett/55997800/1 |title=Ariel Hsing is table tennis prodigy with influential fans |last=Florek |first=Michael |date=July 3, 2012 |work=USA Today |accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/video/warren-buffett-olympic-discovery/C79C0DFF-3687-4894-AFD2-047AFC2E12DB.html |title=Warren Buffett's Olympic Discovery |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=May 3, 2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> Since then, Ariel has been invited to the Berkshire Hathaway Annual Shareholders Meeting to play table tennis with Warren Buffett, Bill Gates, and the stockholders.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.omaha.com/money/warren-buffett-and-bill-gates-try-their-hand-at-table/article_93382bf4-f1eb-11e4-a076-83613e06e61b.html |title=Warren Buffett and Bill Gates try their hand at table tennis |newspaper=[[Omaha World-Herald]] |date=May 4, 2015 |accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> Gates was present during Hsing's Round of 32 loss during the 2012 Olympics and hugged her as she left the court.<ref name=\"2012 World Rankings\" />\n\nOn July 9, 2012, she appeared on an episode of the [[Nickelodeon]] [[game show]] ''[[Figure It Out]]''. She stumped panelists [[Ciara Bravo]], [[Alex Heartman]], [[Leon Thomas III]] and [[Stephen Kramer Glickman]], for one round.\n\n== 2012 London Olympics ==\n[[File:Ariel Hing in London 2012.jpg|thumb|Ariel Hing in London during the 2012 Olympics]]\n\nHsing entered the Olympics as the 46th seed <ref name=\"2012 seeds\" /> and ranked 115th in the world.<ref name=\"2012 World Rankings\">{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Toby |title=Gates flies in to hail \"amazing\" Hsing |url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/table-tennis/gates-flies-in-to-hail-amazing-hsing.html |work=NBC Olympics |accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the round of 128 Hsing defeated [[Yadira Silva]] in 4 games (11-9, 11-8, 11-3, 11-5) in a match where she never trailed by more than 2 points.\nIn the round of 64 Hsing defeated [[Ni Xia Lian]] of Luxembourg 4-2 (11-9, 10-12, 11-9, 11-5, 10-12, 12-10),\nIn the round of 32 Hsing lost to the #2 seed and eventual gold medalist [[Li Xiaoxia]] of China 4-2 (11-4, 9-11, 11-6, 6-11, 11-8, 11-9) with the longest rally of 18 occurring in game 6.\n\nAfter the loss Hsing said it was the best she had ever performed at a tournament giving herself a \"10 out of 10, or maybe 9.9 as I wasn't quite there.\"<ref name=\"2012 World Rankings\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nHsing has been blogging for espnW for her Olympic journey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/athletes-life/article/7558315/ariel-hsing-hopes-training-take-olympics |title=Hsing hopes training will take her to Olympics |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=February 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Olympics, Hsing was selected as the 2012 Female High School Athlete of the year by San Jose Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vcs.net/cf_news/view.cfm?newsid=273 |title=Ariel Hsing to be Honored by San Jose Sports Authority as Female Athlete of the Year |publisher=vcs.net |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHsing graduated from [[Valley Christian High School (San Jose, California)|Valley Christian High School]] in [[San Jose, CA|San Jose]] in 2013. She is a graduate of [[Princeton University]]<ref>Rolston, Dorian [http://paw.princeton.edu/issues/2014/02/05/pages/7604/index.xml \"Bullwhip backhands: A national champion as a freshman, Hsing looks to another Olympic run\"] ''Princeton Alumni Weekly'', February 5, 2014</ref> and was elected as Social Chair for the Class of 2017. Hsing speaks both [[English language|English]] and [[Mandarin Chinese]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Purdy, Mark |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_21188835/mark-purdy-san-joses-ariel-hsing-makes-most |title=Mark Purdy: San Jose's Ariel Hsing makes most of her Olympic moments at London Games |newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]] |date=July 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe is featured in the documentary ''[[Top Spin (documentary)|Top Spin]]'' directed by Mina T. Son and Sara Newens.\n\nAriel participated in Andy Akiho's Ping Pong Concerto, world premiered in Shanghai on July 18, 2015, at Shanghai Symphony Hall by [[Shanghai Symphony Orchestra]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.camimusic.com/news-blog/2015/11/9/shanghai-symphony-orchestra-world-premiered-ping-pong-concerto-ricochet-on-music-in-the-summer-air-misa-festival |title=Shanghai Symphony Orchestra world premiered Ping Pong Concerto (RICOCHET) on Music in the Summer Air (MISA) Festival |newspaper=Cami Music |access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref> Ping Pong Concerto has also performed in Beijing, Guangzhou, Foshan, and is scheduled to perform in London and Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hkphil.org/eng/concerts_and_ticket/concerts/concertdetail.jsp?id=570 |title=Ping Pong Diplomacy - Hong Kong Philharmonic |publisher=HKPhil |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAriel is a contributing author of \"2 Billion Under 20: How Millennials Are Breaking Down Age Barriers and Changing the World\" by [[Stacey Ferreira]] and Jared Kleinert, which became the #1 New Release in Business Leadership on Amazon.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Billion-Under-20-Millennials-Breaking/dp/1250067618 |title=2 Billion Under 20: How Millennials Are Breaking Down Age Barriers and Changing the World |publisher=amazon |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, with her independent study of \"Chinese Stock Market Anomalies: An Empirical Analysis,\u201d Ariel was selected by China Hands Magazine as the 25 under 25: Leaders in U.S.-China Relations, which \"profiles 25 students and professionals under the age of 25 who have demonstrated exceptional promise in China studies and in furthering the future of the U.S.-China relationship.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://chinahandsmagazine.org/2017/01/17/2016-25-under-25-leaders-in-u-s-china-relations/amp/ |title=2016 25 Under 25: Leaders in U.S.-China Relations |publisher=chinahandsmag |accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Competition records<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialarielhsing.com/ariels-milestones/ |title=ARIEL\u2019S MILESTONES |publisher=officialarielhsing.com |accessdate=January 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201235934/http://www.officialarielhsing.com/ariels-milestones/ |archive-date=February 1, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>==\n\n*2015 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Team Champion (Princeton University)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/article/2015/04/table-tennis-triumphs-at-nationals |title=Table tennis triumphs at Nationals |publisher=dailyprincetonian.com |accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n*2015 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Doubles Champion\n*2014 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Team Champion (Princeton University)\n*2014 North American Collegiate Championship \u2013 Women's Singles Champion\n*2013 North American Championship \u2013 Women's Singles Champion\n*2013 North American Championship \u2013 Junior Girls' Team Champion\n*2013 North American Championship \u2013 Junior Girls' Singles Champion\n*2013 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles, Mixed Doubles, Women's U21-Silver  \n*2012 ITTF Intercontinental Cup \u2013 Women's Champion\n*2012 North America Cup \u2013 Women's Champion\n*2012 ITTF Brazil Open \u2013 Women's U21 Champion\n*2012 ITTF USA Junior & Cadet Open \u2013 Junior Girls Singles, Doubles, and Team Champions.\n*2011 North American Championship and Cup Women's Champion\n*2011 ITTF Junior Circuit Finals \u2013 Girls Singles 3rd place.\n*2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women Team Bronze medalist\n*2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women Singles Bronze medalist\n*2011 JUIC International Jr. & Cadet \u2013  Open Champion\n*2011 Canadian Junior Open \u2013  Team and doubles Champion, Single 2nd\n*2010 ITTF Global Cadet Challenge \u2013 Girls Single 3rd place\n*2010 ITTF Global Cadet Challenge \u2013 Girls Doubles 2nd place\n*2010 Inaugural Youth Olympic Games \u2013 USA representative\n*2010 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2010 North America Championship \u2013 Junior Girls 2nd place\n*2010 North America Championship Junior Girls Team Champion\n*2010 China vs. World Team Challenge \u2013 Represented Junior Girls World team finished 2nd place.\n*2010 Italian Junior & Cadet Open \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles Champion\n*2010 Italian Junior & Cadet Open \u2013 Cadet Girls Doubles Champion\n*2010 Safir International \u2013 Girls Under 16 Champion\n*2010 PanAm Youth Olymplics Trial in El Salvador \u2013 Girls First Place\n*2009 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2009 North America Championship \u2013 Junior Girls singles Champion\n*2009 North America Championship Junior Girls Team Champion\n*2009 Pan American ITTF Cadet Challenge Trial Champion\n*2009 Canadian Junior open Cadet Champion\n*2009 Canadian Junior open Cadet Doubles Champion\n*2009 Canadian Junior open Junior Team Champion\n*2008 Pan American Junior Girls champion\n*2008 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2008 North America Championship \u2013 Junior Girls singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Junior Girls Singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and Under Singles Champion\n*2007 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and under Singles Champion\n*2007 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls singles Champion\n*2007 North America Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Team Champion\n*2006 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and Under Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 15 and under Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 13 and under Singles Champion\n*2006 U.S. Open Championship \u2013 Girls 11 and under Singles Champion\n*2005 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Cadet Girls Singles 2nd place\n*2005 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girl 10 and under Singles Champion\n*2005 Junior National under 10 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior National under 12 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior National under 14 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior Olympic under 10 Girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior Olympic under 12 Girl double: Gold\n*2005 Junior Olympic team under 16 girls: Gold\n*2005 Junior National/Olympic Joel Ferrell Sportsmanship Award\n*2004 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girl 10 and under Singles Champion\n*2003 U.S. National Championship \u2013 Girl 10 and under Singles Champion\n\n== References ==\n[[File:Ariel Hsing.jpg|right|thumb|Hsing playing at the 2007 [[Berkshire Hathaway]] shareholders meeting in [[Omaha, Nebraska]], USA.]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ITTF|111120}}\n** {{Cite web |url=http://www.ittfranking.com/cgi-bin/ttplayer.cgi?number=111120&lang=0&format=summary |title=Ariel Hsing at ittfranking.com |access-date=June 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719111711/http://www.ittfranking.com/cgi-bin/ttplayer.cgi?number=111120&lang=0&format=summary |archive-date=July 19, 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown }}\n* {{IOC profile|ariel-hsing}}\n* {{USOC profile|HS/Ariel-Hsing}}\n\n{{Footer North American Champions Table Tennis Singles Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hsing, Ariel}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female table tennis players]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Olympic table tennis players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Fremont, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Alameda County, California]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2011 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of Northern Han Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in table tennis]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2012 London Olympics:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 11-8 \u2192 11\u20138 (8)", "url_pa